WEBVTT

00:00.749 --> 00:03.292
[bright tone]

00:04.749 --> 00:07.666
[funky bass line]

00:07.749 --> 00:12.958
♪ ♪

00:13.041 --> 00:15.958
[remix of "Stayin' Alive"]

00:16.041 --> 00:17.583
[funky disco music]

00:17.666 --> 00:20.375
- ♪ Well, you can tell
by the way I use my walk ♪

00:20.458 --> 00:23.000
♪ ♪

00:23.083 --> 00:25.333
♪ Music loud ♪

00:25.417 --> 00:27.333
♪ Kicked around ♪

00:27.417 --> 00:29.833
♪ And now it's all right,
it's okay ♪

00:29.916 --> 00:32.125
♪ And you may look
the other way ♪

00:32.208 --> 00:34.499
♪ We can try to understand ♪

00:34.583 --> 00:36.875
♪ "The New York Times'"
effect on man ♪

00:36.958 --> 00:38.666
♪ ♪

00:38.749 --> 00:39.833
[siren wails]

00:39.916 --> 00:41.583
♪ ♪

00:41.666 --> 00:43.875
♪ Ah, ha, ha, ha ♪

00:43.958 --> 00:50.875
♪ Stayin' alive ♪

00:50.958 --> 00:54.499
♪ ♪

00:54.583 --> 00:56.583
[indistinct chatter]

00:56.666 --> 00:58.749
[crowd cheering]

00:58.833 --> 01:00.749
- Okay, fellas,
when you're ready.

01:00.833 --> 01:02.083
Okay, fellas, get back in line.

01:02.167 --> 01:03.250
- How did you people get
back here?

01:03.333 --> 01:04.541
Come on. Come on.
Sorry.

01:04.624 --> 01:05.875
- Excuse me.
Have you got a pen?

01:05.958 --> 01:07.167
- I'm sorry,
you can't come in here.

01:07.250 --> 01:08.666
- Get him out of here.
- You can't come in here.

01:08.749 --> 01:10.833
What are you doing?
This is a private session!

01:10.916 --> 01:12.541
[crowd cheering]

01:12.624 --> 01:15.041
- Thank you.

01:15.125 --> 01:18.583
Thank you very, very much.
Good evening to all of you.

01:18.666 --> 01:19.875
Thank you.

01:19.958 --> 01:22.833
["How Can You Mend
a Broken Heart?"]

01:22.916 --> 01:24.583
[soft ballad]

01:24.666 --> 01:28.833
- ♪ I can think
of younger days ♪

01:28.916 --> 01:31.958
♪ When living for my life ♪

01:32.041 --> 01:36.250
♪ Was everything a man
could want to do ♪

01:36.333 --> 01:42.624
♪ I could never see tomorrow ♪

01:42.708 --> 01:45.250
♪ No one said a word ♪

01:45.333 --> 01:50.083
♪ About the sorrow ♪

01:50.167 --> 01:51.749
- ♪ And ♪

01:51.833 --> 01:54.624
♪ How can you mend ♪

01:54.708 --> 01:58.958
♪ A broken heart? ♪

01:59.041 --> 02:00.791
♪ How can you stop the rain ♪

02:00.875 --> 02:04.250
♪ From falling down? ♪

02:04.333 --> 02:07.791
all: ♪ How can you stop ♪

02:07.875 --> 02:10.583
♪ The sun from shining? ♪

02:10.666 --> 02:15.250
♪ What makes the world
go round? ♪

02:15.333 --> 02:19.958
♪ Na, na, na-na-na-na ♪

02:20.041 --> 02:23.458
♪ Na-na-na-na-na ♪

02:23.541 --> 02:26.292
♪ Na-na-na-na ♪

02:26.375 --> 02:29.083
♪ Na-na-na ♪

02:29.167 --> 02:32.791
♪ Please help me mend ♪

02:32.875 --> 02:36.916
♪ My broken heart ♪

02:37.000 --> 02:41.125
- ♪ And let me live again ♪

02:41.208 --> 02:45.125
[cheers and applause]
♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪

02:45.208 --> 02:49.499
♪ Da-da-da-da ♪

02:49.583 --> 02:55.541
♪ Da-da-da-da-da-da ♪

02:55.624 --> 03:02.624
♪ ♪

03:13.250 --> 03:15.666
I am beginning
to recognize the fact

03:15.749 --> 03:18.666
that nothing is true.

03:18.749 --> 03:20.499
Nothing.

03:20.583 --> 03:22.458
It's all down to perception.

03:24.250 --> 03:26.375
My immediate family is gone.

03:26.458 --> 03:28.541
But that's life.

03:28.624 --> 03:30.208
It's the same thing
with every family,

03:30.292 --> 03:32.292
that someone will be left
in the end.

03:34.958 --> 03:36.916
And this time of life,

03:37.000 --> 03:39.541
I have fantastic memories,

03:39.624 --> 03:41.875
but everybody's memory
is different,

03:41.958 --> 03:44.499
so they're just my memories,
you know?

03:46.292 --> 03:48.000
I know that Maurice
and Robin would've had

03:48.083 --> 03:50.541
a different kind of memory.

03:50.624 --> 03:51.708
[projector whirring]

03:51.791 --> 03:53.541
[Richard Swift's "Lady Luck"]

03:53.624 --> 03:56.083
- ♪ One, two, three, four ♪

03:56.167 --> 03:57.208
♪ ♪

03:57.292 --> 03:59.208
- I remember Barry saying
that one day,

03:59.292 --> 04:01.250
we're gonna be really famous.

04:01.333 --> 04:04.041
And we said, "Oh, yeah."
You know, "Whatever you say."

04:04.125 --> 04:06.541
He's the big brother, you know.

04:06.624 --> 04:08.417
- ♪ Ooh ♪

04:08.499 --> 04:10.083
- We kind of saw ourselves
as triplets

04:10.167 --> 04:12.250
rather than me and Maurice
being twins,

04:12.333 --> 04:14.749
and we always had
the same goals growing up

04:14.833 --> 04:16.666
that it became impossible
to see each other

04:16.749 --> 04:19.250
as normal brothers.

04:19.333 --> 04:20.916
- My ninth Christmas,

04:21.000 --> 04:22.958
there was an acoustic guitar
at the end of my bed,

04:23.041 --> 04:25.083
and Robin and Maurice started
to collaborate

04:25.167 --> 04:26.791
and pretend to sing with me,

04:26.875 --> 04:30.333
and we started doing gigs
as a teenage act.

04:30.417 --> 04:31.499
♪ I, O ♪

04:31.583 --> 04:33.083
- We emigrated
as a whole family

04:33.167 --> 04:35.250
from England
to Australia.

04:35.333 --> 04:37.083
- All three of us had
the same understanding

04:37.167 --> 04:38.417
that we were going
to be famous

04:38.499 --> 04:39.958
come hell or high water.

04:40.041 --> 04:43.250
♪ You know I love getting up
in the morning ♪

04:43.333 --> 04:47.083
♪ When the sun first strikes
the trees ♪

04:47.167 --> 04:48.958
Our father,
he had his own band,

04:49.041 --> 04:52.208
but it didn't work out,
so he became our manager,

04:52.292 --> 04:53.250
and it was a team.

04:53.333 --> 04:54.749
There was us three and Dad.

04:54.833 --> 04:56.125
And Mum, of course.

04:56.208 --> 04:58.417
- My mother,
she was always the person

04:58.499 --> 05:00.791
who kept the calm
between Dad and us.

05:00.875 --> 05:03.417
Very strong, very loyal.

05:03.499 --> 05:04.417
["How Many Birds"]

05:04.499 --> 05:05.417
[crowd screaming]

05:05.499 --> 05:06.958
- The Beatles
have just arrived

05:07.041 --> 05:08.833
for the first time
in our country.

05:08.916 --> 05:10.375
- When the Beatles came
on the scene,

05:10.458 --> 05:13.250
it was like, "That's what
we've been trying to do."

05:13.333 --> 05:14.916
- They turned pop music
into an art form,

05:15.000 --> 05:16.458
and they were singing
three-part harmony

05:16.541 --> 05:17.666
like we did.

05:17.749 --> 05:19.083
- So we made up our own minds

05:19.167 --> 05:22.125
that we were going back to be
part of the British Invasion.

05:22.208 --> 05:23.916
- Making music was
what we wanted to do

05:24.000 --> 05:25.458
for the rest of our lives,

05:25.541 --> 05:27.499
so we thought, you know,
whatever's going to happen,

05:27.583 --> 05:29.958
we'll make happen.

05:30.041 --> 05:33.292
["Spicks and Specks"]

05:33.375 --> 05:35.208
- ♪ Where is the sun ♪

05:35.292 --> 05:37.083
Before we left Australia,

05:37.167 --> 05:39.167
we did an album
called "Spicks and Specks,"

05:39.250 --> 05:41.208
and they became
our best demos.

05:41.292 --> 05:43.292
♪ The sun in my life ♪

05:43.375 --> 05:45.666
♪ It is dead ♪

05:45.749 --> 05:47.708
Dad and I did the rounds,

05:47.791 --> 05:49.167
met with industry people,

05:49.250 --> 05:50.708
and as we sat
in everyone's office,

05:50.791 --> 05:52.292
they would say the same thing:

05:52.375 --> 05:55.000
"No, no, I'm sorry, lads.
We can't help you."

05:55.083 --> 05:57.708
- My dad, he was very,
you know, "We gotta do this."

05:57.791 --> 06:00.000
Because my dad was really
the most ambitious man,

06:00.083 --> 06:02.000
I think, in the Gibb clan.

06:02.083 --> 06:03.250
- We loved the Beatles,

06:03.333 --> 06:05.624
so Dad had sent this stuff
to NEMS,

06:05.708 --> 06:08.292
the Brian Epstein offices.

06:08.375 --> 06:10.499
- Brian Epstein,
the man who built the Beatles

06:10.583 --> 06:11.833
into a cult,

06:11.916 --> 06:13.791
is now as well-known
as they are.

06:13.875 --> 06:17.167
- I was doing Brian's mail
most of the time.

06:17.250 --> 06:18.875
There was a letter
by the father

06:18.958 --> 06:22.666
of these three handsome,
cute guys

06:22.749 --> 06:26.250
who were very proactive
and who'd had some success.

06:26.333 --> 06:27.541
They came from Manchester,

06:27.624 --> 06:30.208
but they were writing
from Australia.

06:30.292 --> 06:31.708
I showed it to him.

06:31.791 --> 06:33.875
Brian said, "Yeah, yeah.
That's very nice. No, nice."

06:33.958 --> 06:35.833
He said,
"Well, give it to Robert."

06:35.916 --> 06:36.875
["Wine and Women"]

06:36.958 --> 06:38.583
"He's Australian

06:38.666 --> 06:40.583
and he's good
at these kind of things."

06:40.666 --> 06:41.749
- Somebody sent you a tape

06:41.833 --> 06:43.541
of these boys
from Australia?

06:43.624 --> 06:44.666
- Yes, they did.

06:44.749 --> 06:46.541
- Oh.
[laughter]

06:46.624 --> 06:50.708
- I heard it, and I was
absolutely astounded.

06:50.791 --> 06:52.708
It was the most brilliant
harmony singing

06:52.791 --> 06:54.875
and composing I'd ever heard.

06:54.958 --> 06:56.791
all: ♪ If this should end ♪

06:56.875 --> 06:59.250
♪ I don't mind ♪

06:59.333 --> 07:00.875
♪ If this should end ♪

07:00.958 --> 07:04.417
♪ I will find ♪

07:04.499 --> 07:06.583
- ♪ What shall I do? ♪

07:06.666 --> 07:08.458
both: ♪ What shall I do? ♪

07:08.541 --> 07:10.458
- ♪ What shall I do? ♪

07:10.541 --> 07:12.624
both: ♪ What shall I do? ♪

07:12.708 --> 07:14.250
♪ ♪

07:14.333 --> 07:17.250
- At the time,
Robert was my manager.

07:17.333 --> 07:20.125
Cream was signed to Robert

07:20.208 --> 07:22.417
on what I thought
was an exclusive deal.

07:22.499 --> 07:26.250
I was surprised that
other bands were coming in.

07:26.333 --> 07:27.791
all: ♪ If this should end ♪

07:27.875 --> 07:29.833
- Robert was so eccentric.

07:29.916 --> 07:32.417
I mean, absolutely bonkers.

07:32.499 --> 07:35.875
He was Australian, but he spoke
like an English gentleman,

07:35.958 --> 07:38.499
and he would wear
these really big, flashy ties,

07:38.583 --> 07:41.958
and he had a combover,
and it was all--

07:42.041 --> 07:43.624
who is this guy?

07:43.708 --> 07:46.083
- Whoever this man was,
he really believed in us.

07:46.167 --> 07:48.167
He was almost like a parent.

07:48.250 --> 07:50.666
- You can't deny talent,

07:50.749 --> 07:53.458
and the talent was so obvious.

07:53.541 --> 07:56.666
all: ♪ Ooh ♪

07:56.749 --> 07:58.583
♪ ♪

07:58.666 --> 08:01.458
- Somebody mentioned that
the Bee Gees were in town.

08:01.541 --> 08:05.208
They were good friends of mine
from Australia.

08:05.292 --> 08:07.624
So I phoned them up.

08:07.708 --> 08:08.916
I said, "Is Maurice there,
then?

08:09.000 --> 08:10.125
Put Maurice on."
[champagne cork pops]

08:10.208 --> 08:11.958
He said,
"We've being signed up

08:12.041 --> 08:13.958
"by this guy
called Robert Stigwood.

08:14.041 --> 08:15.749
"We're doing this recording.

08:15.833 --> 08:18.083
Why don't you come
and play guitar?"

08:18.167 --> 08:22.125
Caught a train into London
and found IBC Studios.

08:22.208 --> 08:23.499
So there they were.

08:23.583 --> 08:25.292
There were Barry, Robin,
and Maurice

08:25.375 --> 08:28.000
and the drummer,
Colin Petersen.

08:28.083 --> 08:29.041
That night,

08:29.125 --> 08:32.167
my life changed completely.

08:32.250 --> 08:34.083
Completely.

08:35.541 --> 08:36.499
- The first evening
we were in there,

08:36.583 --> 08:38.167
there was a blackout.

08:38.250 --> 08:40.125
So while we were waiting
for the power to come back on,

08:40.208 --> 08:41.125
we just sat on the steps,

08:41.208 --> 08:43.000
and Barry was playing
his guitar.

08:43.083 --> 08:44.666
It was so echoey.

08:44.749 --> 08:47.167
I mean, it was a wonderful echo
in this place.

08:47.250 --> 08:48.666
- There we were in the dark.

08:48.749 --> 08:50.041
The first thought was,
"In the event

08:50.125 --> 08:51.208
of something happening to me."

08:51.292 --> 08:52.708
both: ♪ In the event ♪

08:52.791 --> 08:55.624
♪ Of something happening
to me ♪

08:55.708 --> 08:57.541
- And we thought, "Well,
what could come from that?"

08:57.624 --> 09:01.708
both: ♪ There is something
I would like you all to see ♪

09:01.791 --> 09:02.958
- We made believe
we were in a mine.

09:03.041 --> 09:08.375
both: ♪ It's just a photograph
of someone that I knew ♪

09:08.458 --> 09:14.041
all: ♪ Have you seen my wife,
Mr. Jones? ♪

09:14.125 --> 09:19.041
♪ Do you know what it's like
on the outside? ♪

09:19.125 --> 09:24.000
♪ Don't go talking too loud,
you'll cause a landslide ♪

09:24.083 --> 09:26.541
♪ Mr. Jones ♪

09:26.624 --> 09:28.041
- Because it was gonna be
our first single,

09:28.125 --> 09:29.875
we wanted a title
that captured the imagination,

09:29.958 --> 09:31.749
that got people's attention.

09:31.833 --> 09:34.000
- And "New York Mining
Disaster" was born then.

09:34.083 --> 09:36.417
- We had our first hit record
within the first five months

09:36.499 --> 09:37.666
of being in England.

09:37.749 --> 09:39.875
The thrill was that it did
the same thing in America.

09:39.958 --> 09:41.499
We thought that we might get
a hit in England,

09:41.583 --> 09:42.875
but we never dreamed
that we might get a hit

09:42.958 --> 09:44.458
in England and America as well.

09:44.541 --> 09:47.458
[Otis Redding's "Respect"]

09:47.541 --> 09:49.375
♪ ♪

09:49.458 --> 09:51.250
- So I came over
to the United States

09:51.333 --> 09:53.417
to make a record deal for them.

09:53.499 --> 09:57.583
I made a decision to place
the group with Atlantic.

09:57.666 --> 09:59.250
- ♪ What you want ♪

09:59.333 --> 10:00.458
♪ Honey, you got it ♪

10:00.541 --> 10:02.417
- He said, "I'm taking you
to meet Ahmet Ertegun

10:02.499 --> 10:05.250
and to get you into
the American music scene."

10:05.333 --> 10:08.417
Otis Redding was playing
at the Apollo.

10:08.499 --> 10:09.791
Ahmet Ertegun
and Robert Stigwood

10:09.875 --> 10:11.708
took me down there
to see Otis.

10:11.791 --> 10:13.749
- ♪ Hey, hey, hey ♪

10:13.833 --> 10:15.375
- And it was amazing.

10:15.458 --> 10:17.958
- Soul has always had
a special place

10:18.041 --> 10:19.125
in the Bee Gees' music.

10:19.208 --> 10:20.916
- We've always been influenced
by Black music.

10:21.000 --> 10:23.208
Smokey Robinson, Motown,

10:23.292 --> 10:25.250
all that was a big influence
on us.

10:25.333 --> 10:26.833
- Robert introduced us.

10:26.916 --> 10:30.458
He said, "I want you to write
a song for Otis Redding."

10:30.541 --> 10:32.458
"To Love Somebody" was born
that night.

10:32.541 --> 10:34.624
- ♪ Hey, hey, hey ♪

10:34.708 --> 10:36.583
- But unfortunately,

10:36.666 --> 10:38.458
Otis never got to record
the song.

10:38.541 --> 10:41.458
["To Love Somebody"]

10:41.541 --> 10:42.916
[soulful ballad]

10:43.000 --> 10:46.791
♪ There's a light ♪

10:46.875 --> 10:49.749
♪ A certain kind of light ♪

10:49.833 --> 10:52.333
♪ That never shone on me ♪

10:52.417 --> 10:54.958
♪ ♪

10:55.041 --> 10:58.292
♪ I want my life to be ♪

10:58.375 --> 11:00.916
♪ Lived with you ♪

11:01.000 --> 11:03.125
♪ Lived with you ♪

11:03.208 --> 11:05.292
- I mean,
I must have always known

11:05.375 --> 11:06.958
"To Love Somebody,"

11:07.041 --> 11:10.000
'cause that song is just,
like, in the ether.

11:10.083 --> 11:11.791
Those lyrics, "There's
a certain kind of light

11:11.875 --> 11:13.000
that never shone on me,"

11:13.083 --> 11:14.666
like, I don't even know
if he's talking about himself,

11:14.749 --> 11:17.125
but there was some point
where I got obsessed,

11:17.208 --> 11:19.000
like, tracking down
every cover version,

11:19.083 --> 11:21.499
like Nina Simone, the Animals.

11:21.583 --> 11:23.833
Some great singers have sung
that song, obviously,

11:23.916 --> 11:26.208
but his vocal,
when he sings it,

11:26.292 --> 11:28.499
I can still get chills
thinking about it.

11:28.583 --> 11:29.833
- ♪ Baby ♪

11:29.916 --> 11:34.333
all: ♪ You don't know
what it's like ♪

11:34.417 --> 11:39.167
♪ Baby, you don't know
what it's like ♪

11:39.250 --> 11:41.791
♪ To love somebody ♪

11:41.875 --> 11:44.499
♪ To love somebody ♪

11:44.583 --> 11:47.875
♪ The way I love you ♪

11:47.958 --> 11:50.541
- ♪ Aw, no, no ♪

11:50.624 --> 11:54.375
both: ♪ You don't know ♪
all: ♪ What it's like ♪

11:54.458 --> 11:58.041
- I just remember
this music being on,

11:58.125 --> 12:00.041
and I'm like, "Who's this?"

12:00.125 --> 12:03.375
And, "Why, it's the Bee Gees."

12:03.458 --> 12:04.833
And I was like, "The Bee Gees?"

12:04.916 --> 12:06.833
["In My Own Time"]

12:06.916 --> 12:08.749
It actually blew my mind.

12:08.833 --> 12:12.208
Those early records sound like
the Beatles' early records.

12:12.292 --> 12:15.833
- ♪ I received an invitation ♪

12:15.916 --> 12:18.375
- It's classic '60s guitar
pop sound,

12:18.458 --> 12:19.749
but then it had another thing
going on.

12:19.833 --> 12:23.208
- ♪ "Come
to the United Nations" ♪

12:23.292 --> 12:25.167
- You've got
the brothers singing,

12:25.250 --> 12:27.167
and when you've got
brothers singing,

12:27.250 --> 12:29.541
it's like an instrument
that nobody else can buy.

12:29.624 --> 12:32.958
- ♪ That was when
I was somebody ♪

12:33.041 --> 12:35.916
[bouncy rock music]

12:36.000 --> 12:40.791
all: ♪ In my own time ♪

12:40.875 --> 12:43.250
- You can't go buy that sound
in a shop.

12:43.333 --> 12:44.499
You can buy
a Fender Stratocaster

12:44.583 --> 12:47.916
and put it through a VOX amp
and sound like Buddy Holly.

12:48.000 --> 12:49.417
You can't sing
like the Bee Gees,

12:49.499 --> 12:50.583
because when you've got

12:50.666 --> 12:52.125
family members
singing together,

12:52.208 --> 12:53.708
it's unique.

12:53.791 --> 12:56.875
- It's the blend of the tones
of each brother.

12:56.958 --> 13:00.250
And Robin had this wonderful,
tear-jerking voice.

13:00.333 --> 13:02.749
["I Started a Joke"]

13:02.833 --> 13:04.458
[somber ballad]

13:04.541 --> 13:06.250
- Robin was a joyous kid.

13:06.333 --> 13:08.083
Hysterically funny.

13:08.167 --> 13:10.749
He took great joy
in being on television.

13:10.833 --> 13:13.167
This was the funniest kid
you could ever meet.

13:13.250 --> 13:14.958
- My father always used
to call him the nanny goat.

13:15.041 --> 13:16.791
'Cause Robin would go...
[silly vocalization]

13:16.875 --> 13:18.458
He'd be rehearsing
in the back of the car,

13:18.541 --> 13:19.791
you know,
doing all these phases

13:19.875 --> 13:21.624
and, you know...
♪ I love you-ooh ♪

13:21.708 --> 13:22.958
And he'd go, "Shut up!

13:23.041 --> 13:24.250
You sound like
a bloody nanny goat."

13:24.333 --> 13:25.958
♪ ♪

13:26.041 --> 13:29.624
- ♪ I started a joke ♪

13:29.708 --> 13:34.833
♪ Which started
the whole world crying ♪

13:34.916 --> 13:37.458
- Robin was always
a bit of a loner.

13:37.541 --> 13:39.666
- I like being spontaneous.

13:39.749 --> 13:40.833
I like being funny
with people,

13:40.916 --> 13:43.292
but you won't get that
right away with me, you see.

13:43.375 --> 13:46.125
- Robin had a wit that
no one could compete with.

13:46.208 --> 13:47.833
And he could be very dark too.

13:47.916 --> 13:51.292
- ♪ I looked at the skies ♪

13:51.375 --> 13:52.833
- Robin is not a person
who would say,

13:52.916 --> 13:54.167
"Oh, I love my brothers,"

13:54.250 --> 13:56.292
or, "Group hug."

13:56.375 --> 13:57.583
You know, none of that stuff.

13:57.666 --> 13:59.375
- I'm basically
a very shy person.

13:59.458 --> 14:01.167
I'm very hard to get to know.

14:01.250 --> 14:05.000
I have to really know somebody
before I reveal myself.

14:05.083 --> 14:08.875
♪ Till I finally died ♪

14:08.958 --> 14:15.000
♪ Which started
the whole world living ♪

14:15.083 --> 14:18.167
♪ Oh ♪

14:18.250 --> 14:19.499
- You know, I mean,
that's the voice.

14:19.583 --> 14:22.333
That's the voice
that reaches your heart.

14:22.417 --> 14:27.499
♪ ♪

14:27.583 --> 14:29.333
- We did a show
at the Saville Theatre,

14:29.417 --> 14:32.167
and Paul McCartney was there
with Jane Asher,

14:32.250 --> 14:33.458
because Robert had said,

14:33.541 --> 14:35.708
"Would you come
and see the boys?"

14:35.791 --> 14:36.708
- When you think that

14:36.791 --> 14:39.333
five months before all this
was going on,

14:39.417 --> 14:42.499
I was in Pitt Street buying up
the Beatle fan club book,

14:42.583 --> 14:45.250
and now here I am
partying with these guys.

14:45.333 --> 14:47.333
We felt like we'd arrived.

14:47.417 --> 14:49.666
Now I'm living out in Highgate
outside London.

14:49.749 --> 14:51.875
Barry's got a place
in Eaton Square.

14:51.958 --> 14:53.875
Robin's got a house
in St. George's Hill,

14:53.958 --> 14:55.041
beautiful area.

14:55.125 --> 14:57.541
- And Mum and Dad
had their own place,

14:57.624 --> 15:00.083
and, of course, Andy lived
with them.

15:00.167 --> 15:01.708
He was just like us,

15:01.791 --> 15:03.541
and he was always
tagging along,

15:03.624 --> 15:06.041
hoping that one day,
he would do this too.

15:06.125 --> 15:07.541
He would like to sing.

15:07.624 --> 15:09.666
- There was a lot of hits
in that short time,

15:09.749 --> 15:11.083
you know,
and after all the work

15:11.167 --> 15:13.000
we had done through clubs
and everything,

15:13.083 --> 15:14.666
I felt grown up, you know,

15:14.749 --> 15:16.208
so we made the most of it.

15:16.292 --> 15:18.292
- Very talented group of men,
the Bee Gees.

15:18.375 --> 15:20.458
- Once again,
the fabulous Bee Gees.

15:20.541 --> 15:22.125
- Here they are, and get
involved with the Bee Gees.

15:22.208 --> 15:23.125
Here they are.

15:23.208 --> 15:25.417
- ♪ I am man
and you are woman ♪

15:25.499 --> 15:26.749
♪ Who needs marriage? ♪

15:26.833 --> 15:29.292
♪ We are humans all ♪

15:29.375 --> 15:30.499
By then, we were flying,

15:30.583 --> 15:33.541
you know, just the most
amazing experience.

15:33.624 --> 15:35.875
♪ Then it would please you
if I should call ♪

15:35.958 --> 15:37.417
♪ ♪

15:37.499 --> 15:39.417
♪ Doesn't matter
what your name is ♪

15:39.499 --> 15:42.583
♪ I can do a million things
to you ♪

15:42.666 --> 15:43.708
As a pop group,

15:43.791 --> 15:45.749
this was the biggest moment
of our lives.

15:45.833 --> 15:47.250
Never expected.

15:47.333 --> 15:50.083
Hoped for
but never really expected.

15:50.167 --> 15:52.624
[drum solo]

15:52.708 --> 15:56.083
♪ ♪

15:56.167 --> 15:58.583
[crowd shouting]

15:58.666 --> 16:00.791
♪ No, no, no ♪

16:00.875 --> 16:02.458
♪ No, no ♪
[tires squealing]

16:02.541 --> 16:04.167
[engine revving]

16:04.250 --> 16:06.458
Then came "Massachusetts."

16:06.541 --> 16:08.791
Robin said, "I've got
this idea for a song."

16:08.875 --> 16:10.666
He sang the melody,

16:10.749 --> 16:13.541
and I just remember
our jaws dropping.

16:13.624 --> 16:17.000
[sweeping ballad]

16:17.083 --> 16:20.250
- ♪ Feel I'm going back ♪

16:20.333 --> 16:23.125
♪ To Massachusetts ♪

16:23.208 --> 16:26.167
♪ ♪

16:26.250 --> 16:29.458
♪ Something's telling me ♪

16:29.541 --> 16:32.292
♪ I must go home ♪

16:32.375 --> 16:34.458
♪ ♪

16:34.541 --> 16:36.833
all: ♪ And the lights ♪

16:36.916 --> 16:39.083
♪ All went down ♪

16:39.167 --> 16:43.375
♪ In Massachusetts ♪

16:43.458 --> 16:46.833
- ♪ The day I left ♪

16:46.916 --> 16:51.833
♪ Her standing on her own ♪

16:51.916 --> 16:55.000
- For me, they connected
from very early on.

16:55.083 --> 16:57.624
"Massachusetts" is probably
the first song,

16:57.708 --> 16:59.541
I think, that really resonates.

16:59.624 --> 17:03.958
There is a gospel quality
to it.

17:04.041 --> 17:06.666
There is a folk quality to it.

17:06.749 --> 17:09.624
I didn't know where the hell
Massachusetts was,

17:09.708 --> 17:11.041
but I found myself
singing that

17:11.125 --> 17:15.167
and translating it
to where I was from.

17:15.250 --> 17:16.417
- Robert runs up and he goes,

17:16.499 --> 17:18.833
"'Massachusetts' has just gone
to number one."

17:18.916 --> 17:20.000
We went, "What?"

17:20.083 --> 17:22.000
To have a number one
in England,

17:22.083 --> 17:23.875
you have no idea
how much we dreamed of this

17:23.958 --> 17:24.875
back in Australia.

17:24.958 --> 17:28.333
- ♪ And Massachusetts ♪

17:28.417 --> 17:33.916
♪ Is one place I have seen ♪

17:34.000 --> 17:36.208
♪ ♪

17:36.292 --> 17:38.875
- "Massachusetts"
from the Bee Gees.

17:38.958 --> 17:41.041
- I met the Bee Gees
at "Top of the Pops."

17:41.125 --> 17:42.541
I was young.

17:42.624 --> 17:45.167
Was I 16?
Maybe I was even 17.

17:45.250 --> 17:48.041
- Top pop girl in America,
top pop girl in Britain,

17:48.125 --> 17:49.583
the one and only Lulu.

17:49.666 --> 17:51.499
- ♪ Some people live
within the world ♪

17:51.583 --> 17:53.583
♪ And some people live
without it ♪

17:53.666 --> 17:55.666
♪ Some people gotta whisper
their love ♪

17:55.749 --> 17:58.541
♪ And some,
they gotta shout it ♪

17:58.624 --> 18:02.083
The Bee Gees were always
in the studio.

18:02.167 --> 18:03.708
They were always recording.

18:03.791 --> 18:05.125
[melodic piano notes]

18:05.208 --> 18:06.583
They would literally go
into the studio

18:06.666 --> 18:08.208
and start writing.

18:08.292 --> 18:11.417
I had never known
anything like that before.

18:11.499 --> 18:12.958
- We don't usually write
our lyrics

18:13.041 --> 18:14.791
till the day we sing them.

18:14.875 --> 18:17.250
We usually write our lyrics
in the studio itself.

18:17.333 --> 18:19.417
That seems to work
through thick and thin.

18:19.499 --> 18:21.250
It always works for us.

18:21.333 --> 18:23.791
- It's very hard to describe
how we write,

18:23.875 --> 18:25.292
but the only way
I can describe

18:25.375 --> 18:28.041
how we work at it
is by becoming one mind.

18:28.125 --> 18:30.208
- Maurice had unique insight

18:30.292 --> 18:32.083
into the way
Robin and I thought.

18:32.167 --> 18:33.708
[experimental piano chords]

18:33.791 --> 18:35.958
He would just be
fiddling around on the piano.

18:36.041 --> 18:38.417
He'd suddenly
play something, and,

18:38.499 --> 18:39.541
"What was that?"

18:39.624 --> 18:41.624
He was trying to please us

18:41.708 --> 18:44.167
and the way that we would all
try to please each other,

18:44.250 --> 18:46.833
and that sometimes was
the birth of a song.

18:46.916 --> 18:48.000
- All of a sudden,
we'll wake each other's

18:48.083 --> 18:49.958
little instincts up
and the melodies come.

18:50.041 --> 18:52.499
It's wonderful
when you hear it taking shape.

18:52.583 --> 18:53.791
Then it all blossoms.

18:53.875 --> 18:55.458
- The third verse
is four bars.

18:55.541 --> 18:56.958
- It's rolling.

18:57.041 --> 18:58.833
- They'd say, "Okay,
we're ready to roll," right?

18:58.916 --> 19:00.791
And they'd play the song,
and I'd work the chords out.

19:00.875 --> 19:02.125
Colin would figure out

19:02.208 --> 19:03.916
what he's gonna do
on the drums.

19:04.000 --> 19:05.583
They'd say, "Right, here we go.

19:05.666 --> 19:07.125
Let's go. Bang, bang, bang."

19:07.208 --> 19:08.167
Down it went.

19:08.250 --> 19:10.458
["Idea"]

19:10.541 --> 19:14.791
And that spontaneity
came out in the songs.

19:14.875 --> 19:17.916
- In those days, you knocked
an album out in three weeks.

19:18.000 --> 19:20.167
I think we had
three albums out in one year.

19:20.250 --> 19:23.333
both: ♪ But that was when
I got an idea ♪

19:23.417 --> 19:26.125
♪ Came like a gun
and shot in my ear ♪

19:26.208 --> 19:27.250
[crowd shouting]

19:27.333 --> 19:28.833
- ♪ Don't you think
it's time you got up ♪

19:28.916 --> 19:31.000
♪ And stood alone? ♪

19:31.083 --> 19:32.125
♪ ♪

19:32.208 --> 19:33.833
- When we went to Europe,

19:33.916 --> 19:36.499
there'd always be
a big bunch of kids outside

19:36.583 --> 19:38.167
waiting for us to arrive.

19:38.250 --> 19:39.833
It was a frightening time,

19:39.916 --> 19:42.375
because they crawled
all over the Mercedes.

19:42.458 --> 19:45.292
They were on the roof.
They were at the window.

19:45.375 --> 19:47.208
It was crazy.

19:47.292 --> 19:48.583
"Hey, guys.

19:48.666 --> 19:50.958
Do you think we're famous?
Could be."

19:51.041 --> 19:51.958
[laughs]

19:52.041 --> 19:54.041
[crowd cheering]

19:54.125 --> 19:55.375
- The Bee Gees,

19:55.458 --> 19:58.333
the most exciting sound
in the world.

19:58.417 --> 19:59.499
["World"]

19:59.583 --> 20:01.833
- ♪ Now ♪

20:01.916 --> 20:04.666
♪ I found ♪

20:04.749 --> 20:07.458
♪ That the world ♪

20:07.541 --> 20:09.833
♪ Is round ♪

20:09.916 --> 20:12.167
- If you've never been famous,

20:12.250 --> 20:13.583
the first time it happens,

20:13.666 --> 20:15.875
it's a very difficult thing
to handle.

20:15.958 --> 20:17.541
You don't know how to behave.

20:17.624 --> 20:19.167
You don't know
how to experience it.

20:19.250 --> 20:22.375
And that affected all of us
in its own way.

20:22.458 --> 20:24.041
[somber rock music]

20:24.125 --> 20:26.417
- I had six Rolls-Royces
before I was 21.

20:26.499 --> 20:27.749
I don't know
where they are now.

20:27.833 --> 20:28.749
[laughs]

20:28.833 --> 20:30.375
But I mean,
that's how crazy it was.

20:30.458 --> 20:33.125
- We were all very selfish
at that point.

20:33.208 --> 20:35.833
The testosterone kicked in,

20:35.916 --> 20:38.041
and the competition
of life began.

20:38.125 --> 20:40.041
["I've Gotta Get a Message
to You"]

20:40.125 --> 20:41.250
[mellow music]

20:41.333 --> 20:45.791
♪ I told him I'm in no hurry ♪

20:45.875 --> 20:48.417
♪ But if I broke her heart ♪

20:48.499 --> 20:50.499
♪ Then won't you tell her
I'm sorry? ♪

20:50.583 --> 20:54.083
- There was always a conflict
between Barry and Robin

20:54.167 --> 20:56.749
'cause they both had
fantastic voices

20:56.833 --> 20:58.708
and Robin wanted
to sing the song

20:58.791 --> 21:00.041
and Barry wanted to sing it.

21:00.125 --> 21:05.083
both: ♪ I've just gotta get
a message to you ♪

21:05.167 --> 21:07.791
all: ♪ Hold on ♪

21:07.875 --> 21:09.916
♪ Hold on ♪

21:10.000 --> 21:12.624
- Both of us wanted to be
individual performers.

21:12.708 --> 21:14.916
We all wanted
individual recognition.

21:15.000 --> 21:18.583
And therein lies the issue.

21:18.666 --> 21:22.333
all: ♪ Hold on ♪

21:22.417 --> 21:26.083
- I'm speaking to you
from a club in Hamburg,

21:26.167 --> 21:27.791
and I'm Barry Gibb
of the Bee Gees.

21:27.875 --> 21:29.083
Robin here.

21:29.167 --> 21:30.958
Robin, we've heard rumors
that the group is splitting up.

21:31.041 --> 21:32.458
Would you like to verify
those rumors?

21:32.541 --> 21:33.749
- If I was to say
that was true,

21:33.833 --> 21:35.749
then I would be
the premier of Russia.

21:35.833 --> 21:37.125
- I don't know.

21:37.208 --> 21:38.250
- Thank you very much,
Mr. Petersen.

21:38.333 --> 21:39.333
How about you, Mr. Melouney?

21:39.417 --> 21:40.791
- Oh, no.
I don't think it is.

21:40.875 --> 21:43.250
- No. No. No.

21:43.333 --> 21:46.125
["Don't Wanna Live
Inside Myself"]

21:46.208 --> 21:50.125
- I always say
that making music

21:50.208 --> 21:52.666
with your family

21:52.749 --> 21:55.916
is equally
the greatest strength

21:56.000 --> 21:57.791
and the greatest weakness
you could ever have

21:57.875 --> 21:59.833
in a musical partnership.

21:59.916 --> 22:01.624
[somber piano ballad]

22:01.708 --> 22:03.958
To get to the top
or near the top,

22:04.041 --> 22:06.250
you've gotta be
incredibly driven,

22:06.333 --> 22:09.167
and what drives you
is your ego.

22:09.250 --> 22:10.666
And when you get there

22:10.749 --> 22:12.958
and everybody's got an ego
about it,

22:13.041 --> 22:15.375
it can be tricky to stay there.

22:15.458 --> 22:17.833
- ♪ I am the searcher ♪

22:17.916 --> 22:22.375
♪ Of my fortunes ♪

22:22.458 --> 22:25.666
♪ I got my right hand ♪

22:25.749 --> 22:28.167
♪ On the wheel ♪

22:28.250 --> 22:30.041
- The three of us stopped
looking inwards to each other

22:30.125 --> 22:31.958
and all started
looking outwards

22:32.041 --> 22:34.666
to what we could be
individually.

22:34.749 --> 22:36.833
"To hell
with what my brothers think."

22:36.916 --> 22:39.499
And each one of us
was thinking that.

22:39.583 --> 22:42.666
both: ♪ Don't wanna live ♪

22:42.749 --> 22:46.000
♪ Inside myself ♪

22:46.083 --> 22:47.292
- To travel the world
when you're young

22:47.375 --> 22:48.458
with a family member

22:48.541 --> 22:50.875
gives you a certain sense
of who you are

22:50.958 --> 22:52.958
and where you've come from
and all that.

22:53.041 --> 22:56.167
So you kind of walk
that tightrope.

22:56.250 --> 22:58.208
- We'd been together
all our lives, don't forget.

22:58.292 --> 22:59.875
- We'd been together
since Robin and I were five,

22:59.958 --> 23:01.417
singing professionally.

23:01.499 --> 23:02.749
You know, it's a lot of years.

23:02.833 --> 23:05.041
- We'd been kids living
together with each other

23:05.125 --> 23:06.708
right up until
the time we arrived

23:06.791 --> 23:09.375
and even after we arrived
in England.

23:09.458 --> 23:14.375
- ♪ Don't wanna live
inside myself ♪

23:14.458 --> 23:15.708
Robin was first to say,

23:15.791 --> 23:18.541
"Well, I'm quitting
the group."

23:18.624 --> 23:22.499
I stopped really knowing Robin

23:22.583 --> 23:26.250
and his personal life
once we became famous.

23:26.333 --> 23:27.708
And the same with Mo.

23:27.791 --> 23:31.375
Our three lives were
three different lives.

23:31.458 --> 23:33.666
We were no longer living
the same life.

23:33.749 --> 23:40.708
♪ ♪

23:40.791 --> 23:42.208
- Brothers...

23:42.292 --> 23:44.749
in general,
it's a very complicated thing,

23:44.833 --> 23:46.875
you know?

23:46.958 --> 23:48.208
Emotions are heightened,

23:48.292 --> 23:52.167
and there's things that go back
to childhood about, you know,

23:52.250 --> 23:54.833
if one kid got more attention
than the other,

23:54.916 --> 23:56.708
and all these things play out

23:56.791 --> 23:58.541
in front of just a small group
of friends,

23:58.624 --> 24:00.875
but when you magnify that
with the whole world,

24:00.958 --> 24:02.791
it changes the game
a little bit.

24:02.875 --> 24:04.875
- Robin, that's a good picture.

24:04.958 --> 24:07.583
That's you, Barry,
Colin, Vince.

24:07.666 --> 24:09.749
- That's correct, yes.
- Do you miss 'em?

24:09.833 --> 24:11.125
- Well, it's not really
a matter

24:11.208 --> 24:12.458
of missing them, really.

24:12.541 --> 24:14.083
But I still see them
on and off, you know,

24:14.167 --> 24:16.125
so that's the way things go.

24:16.208 --> 24:18.000
I'll show you
the studio anyway.

24:18.958 --> 24:21.333
[George Bizet's "Habanera"]

24:21.417 --> 24:24.624
- It was really me and Robin
that were in conflict,

24:24.708 --> 24:26.624
and I think
Maurice was in the middle.

24:26.708 --> 24:28.458
- Story of my life, really.
[laughs]

24:28.541 --> 24:29.499
Barry would call me up
and say,

24:29.583 --> 24:30.666
"Well, can you call Robin
and tell him

24:30.749 --> 24:31.791
if he wants to do this?"

24:31.875 --> 24:33.125
And Robin would go,
"Well, give Barry a call

24:33.208 --> 24:34.292
and let him know
that I'm gonna be over."

24:34.375 --> 24:35.624
I said,
"Robin, you call Barry."

24:35.708 --> 24:36.958
"Barry, you call Robin."

24:37.041 --> 24:39.125
And they both said,
"No, we won't."

24:39.208 --> 24:41.000
And for 18 months,
they never did.

24:41.083 --> 24:42.833
- We had this fascination

24:42.916 --> 24:46.250
with calling
the newspapers up.

24:46.333 --> 24:49.417
You called "NME" or you called
"Disc" or "Music Echo"

24:49.499 --> 24:50.791
and you'd say...
[grumbles]

24:50.875 --> 24:52.583
"Robin said this about me,
and I just wanna be able

24:52.666 --> 24:55.167
to correct the record,"
and all that stuff.

24:55.250 --> 24:57.583
- It was a whole
strange episode of our lives,

24:57.666 --> 25:00.292
but a lot of things
had gone down at that time,

25:00.375 --> 25:04.000
and we needed time apart
to think about them.

25:04.083 --> 25:06.541
- At Caxton Hall,
VIP transport

25:06.624 --> 25:09.208
for very important pop star
Barry Gibb.

25:09.292 --> 25:10.333
He's getting married

25:10.417 --> 25:12.167
to 20-year-old
former Miss Edinburgh

25:12.250 --> 25:13.833
Linda Gray.

25:13.916 --> 25:16.333
[cheery music]

25:16.417 --> 25:18.708
- Their world was crazy
at that time.

25:18.791 --> 25:20.833
You know, at one time,
there was three brothers,

25:20.916 --> 25:24.167
and then all of a sudden,
it was three wives.

25:24.250 --> 25:27.000
- Maurice Gibb and Lulu
became Mr. and Mrs.

25:27.083 --> 25:28.791
at St. James' Parish Church

25:28.875 --> 25:31.333
at Gerrards Cross
in Buckinghamshire.

25:31.417 --> 25:34.541
- You think,
by marrying someone

25:34.624 --> 25:37.375
that you absolutely adore,

25:37.458 --> 25:39.708
you think it's gonna solve
all your problems,

25:39.791 --> 25:41.250
but really...

25:41.333 --> 25:42.499
- At Caxton Hall,

25:42.583 --> 25:45.083
Robin Gibb of the Bee Gees
marries Molly Hullis.

25:45.167 --> 25:46.375
[upbeat rock music]

25:46.458 --> 25:48.541
- Molly was
my first real love.

25:48.624 --> 25:50.417
The first serious one.

25:50.499 --> 25:52.375
But it was
a very traumatic time for me.

25:52.458 --> 25:55.375
[bombastic music]

25:55.458 --> 25:57.583
I went with my manager.

25:57.666 --> 25:59.000
He said, "Look, Robin,

25:59.083 --> 26:00.583
I'm gonna send you
to New Zealand."

26:00.666 --> 26:03.666
He says, "You're doing
the Redwood Park Festival."

26:03.749 --> 26:04.833
So I went there,
and of course,

26:04.916 --> 26:06.583
it was advertised
that the Bee Gees were coming,

26:06.666 --> 26:08.041
not just Robin Gibb, you see.

26:08.125 --> 26:11.708
[crowd shouting]

26:11.791 --> 26:13.833
All right.
Okay.

26:13.916 --> 26:16.208
- How'd you feel last night?

26:16.292 --> 26:17.583
- I have an obligation
to my audience

26:17.666 --> 26:19.041
not to look scared, and...

26:19.125 --> 26:22.250
I can't say
I really felt scared.

26:22.333 --> 26:23.458
I was terrified.
[laughs]

26:25.499 --> 26:29.041
♪ How far am I able to ♪

26:29.125 --> 26:31.417
[microphone feedback whining]

26:31.499 --> 26:34.499
[crowd screaming]

26:37.791 --> 26:40.041
- All three of us
became isolated,

26:40.125 --> 26:44.083
and all three of us
did things to each other

26:44.167 --> 26:46.083
that I think
we're all sorry for.

26:46.167 --> 26:48.916
[soft music]

26:49.000 --> 26:50.083
We loved each other.

26:50.167 --> 26:52.624
There was an enormous amount
of love between us.

26:52.708 --> 26:54.749
Growing up,
we did everything together.

26:54.833 --> 26:57.375
- We often thought
we were triplets.

26:57.458 --> 27:00.125
Because we all had
the same love.

27:00.208 --> 27:01.208
We had the same sense of humor.

27:01.292 --> 27:03.375
We had the same love
of the same kind of music.

27:03.458 --> 27:05.458
- Just typical kids, you know?

27:05.541 --> 27:07.958
But the one thing
that no one else was doing

27:08.041 --> 27:09.458
was that we were singing
in harmony,

27:09.541 --> 27:12.250
and beyond anything else,
that's all we cared about.

27:12.333 --> 27:14.499
♪ ♪

27:14.583 --> 27:16.916
We fell in love
with the Mills Brothers.

27:17.000 --> 27:19.958
They all did something unique
in their own way.

27:20.041 --> 27:20.958
And at the same time,

27:21.041 --> 27:23.000
Robin and I did
two different leads,

27:23.083 --> 27:25.666
and Maurice would always know
where to put that other melody

27:25.749 --> 27:27.000
to make a three-part harmony.

27:27.083 --> 27:29.791
They mirrored
what we wanted to be.

27:29.875 --> 27:32.458
- Do you find you miss
Robin and Maurice musically?

27:32.541 --> 27:33.624
- Yeah.
[chuckles]

27:33.708 --> 27:35.749
Not musically.

27:35.833 --> 27:38.292
I miss them both as brothers.

27:38.375 --> 27:40.749
- Something
about entering the world

27:40.833 --> 27:43.125
from the same place,
I think, has an effect

27:43.208 --> 27:44.916
on your ability
to sing together,

27:45.000 --> 27:49.541
your creative awareness,
and your artistic voice.

27:49.624 --> 27:52.875
- Could we see the Bee Gees
back together again?

27:52.958 --> 27:56.167
- That's a very strong point
that it could be.

27:56.250 --> 27:57.333
I can't say definitely,

27:57.417 --> 27:59.875
but I'd like to see
the Bee Gees again.

27:59.958 --> 28:02.375
[solemn music]

28:02.458 --> 28:05.375
- Mr. Epstein has been
unwell now for some months.

28:05.458 --> 28:07.458
And he's been in the habit
of taking tablets

28:07.541 --> 28:09.208
to help him sleep at night.

28:09.292 --> 28:11.292
He was found
in his second-floor bedroom

28:11.375 --> 28:14.167
just after 2:00 this afternoon
by his housekeeper.

28:14.250 --> 28:17.666
- When Brian died
and we restructured NEMS,

28:17.749 --> 28:19.333
Robert asked to become

28:19.417 --> 28:21.000
a more important
senior executive

28:21.083 --> 28:22.833
for the Beatles,

28:22.916 --> 28:24.708
and that wasn't acceptable
to them,

28:24.791 --> 28:28.250
so he then left the company

28:28.333 --> 28:31.875
and took with him Eric Clapton
and Bee Gees

28:31.958 --> 28:33.833
so he could start off
on his own.

28:33.916 --> 28:35.208
- We were an asset.

28:35.292 --> 28:37.041
We were one of those people
Robert needed

28:37.125 --> 28:39.041
as an element of going public.

28:39.125 --> 28:40.708
[camera shutters snapping]

28:40.791 --> 28:42.375
It was at the launching
of the company

28:42.458 --> 28:43.958
where we started
to communicate again.

28:44.041 --> 28:45.875
[applause]

28:45.958 --> 28:47.916
And once we came back
together again,

28:48.000 --> 28:49.666
we wrote "Lonely Days,"

28:49.749 --> 28:52.875
which reflected the idea
that we'd been broken up.

28:52.958 --> 28:56.708
- We'd always been boys
going up together,

28:56.791 --> 28:59.208
and I think
we came back together as men.

28:59.292 --> 29:01.292
We respected
each other's opinions,

29:01.375 --> 29:02.875
which we didn't before that.

29:02.958 --> 29:05.000
["How Can You Mend
a Broken Heart?"]

29:05.083 --> 29:06.208
If anything,
that was the good thing

29:06.292 --> 29:07.666
about the breakup.

29:07.749 --> 29:09.708
[soft ballad]

29:09.791 --> 29:12.791
♪ I can think
of younger days ♪

29:12.875 --> 29:14.875
- I had already started
a first verse and chorus.

29:14.958 --> 29:17.250
I knew what "How Can You Mend
a Broken Heart?" was,

29:17.333 --> 29:19.125
but then Robin walks in.

29:19.208 --> 29:21.250
I said, "I'm just working
on this song.

29:21.333 --> 29:22.624
Do you wanna do it with me?"

29:22.708 --> 29:23.958
And he went,
"Yeah, of course."

29:24.041 --> 29:29.417
- ♪ I could never see
tomorrow ♪

29:29.499 --> 29:31.458
- We'd been apart
for two years.

29:31.541 --> 29:32.624
If we hadn't been brothers,

29:32.708 --> 29:34.208
we wouldn't have lasted
half an hour.

29:34.292 --> 29:36.250
It just wouldn't have happened.

29:36.333 --> 29:38.583
♪ ♪

29:38.666 --> 29:40.458
♪ And ♪

29:40.541 --> 29:43.458
♪ How can you mend ♪

29:43.541 --> 29:44.875
♪ A broken heart? ♪

29:44.958 --> 29:48.583
Things started to just improve
over time, you know?

29:48.666 --> 29:50.583
♪ How can you stop the rain ♪

29:50.666 --> 29:52.250
♪ From falling down? ♪

29:52.333 --> 29:54.292
We became the Bee Gees again.

29:54.375 --> 29:58.000
all: ♪ How can you stop ♪

29:58.083 --> 30:01.250
♪ The sun from shining? ♪

30:01.333 --> 30:05.292
♪ What makes the world
go round? ♪

30:05.375 --> 30:07.167
♪ ♪

30:07.250 --> 30:08.749
- We came back together,
and we made

30:08.833 --> 30:10.417
two number one records
in America,

30:10.499 --> 30:12.083
so we were on a bit of a high.

30:12.167 --> 30:14.624
♪ ♪

30:14.708 --> 30:17.292
But we were
not really that good

30:17.375 --> 30:20.958
when it came to just doing
anything without a pill,

30:21.041 --> 30:22.791
you know,
or without a drink.

30:22.875 --> 30:24.125
It was destroying us.

30:24.208 --> 30:26.458
all: ♪ My broken heart ♪

30:26.541 --> 30:29.333
And that became the battle,

30:29.417 --> 30:31.833
the fight to survive
being a pop group.

30:31.916 --> 30:35.041
all: ♪ Da-da-da-da ♪

30:35.125 --> 30:39.333
- ♪ Da-da-da-da-da-da ♪

30:39.417 --> 30:42.417
[cheers and applause]

30:47.541 --> 30:50.292
Thank you very, very much
on behalf of my brothers,

30:50.375 --> 30:52.833
Robin

30:52.916 --> 30:56.083
and Maurice,

30:56.167 --> 30:59.417
and this beautiful orchestra,

30:59.499 --> 31:03.208
our lead guitarist,
Alan Kendall...

31:03.292 --> 31:04.333
- Robert Stigwood said,

31:04.417 --> 31:06.333
"The Bee Gees are gonna go
on a tour,

31:06.417 --> 31:08.666
and they want a guitar player
who can play bass as well,"

31:08.749 --> 31:10.666
'cause in those days,

31:10.749 --> 31:14.791
Maurice played bass, but he
would go on piano sometimes.

31:14.875 --> 31:18.499
And so I called him and I said,
"Well, I can't play bass,"

31:18.583 --> 31:21.000
and he said,
"Just say you can play bass,"

31:21.083 --> 31:23.083
so I said, "Okay,
I can play bass."

31:23.167 --> 31:25.875
[mellow rock music]

31:25.958 --> 31:29.250
I'll be honest, I was
very much into the lifestyle.

31:29.333 --> 31:30.541
I just loved
being on the road.

31:30.624 --> 31:33.083
I loved playing music,
chasing women.

31:33.167 --> 31:34.749
♪ ♪

31:34.833 --> 31:36.000
Maurice is so funny,

31:36.083 --> 31:38.041
'cause he was good
at magic tricks,

31:38.125 --> 31:41.208
and he'd like
to drink a little, as I did.

31:41.292 --> 31:43.250
Robin, I never really knew.

31:43.333 --> 31:46.583
I mean, I'd converse with him
but not as much as the others.

31:46.666 --> 31:48.916
And I would bump into him
every now and then

31:49.000 --> 31:51.875
wandering the corridors
of the hotel.

31:51.958 --> 31:55.041
And there's Barry
with his glamorous wife

31:55.125 --> 31:57.083
smoking a bowl, you know?

31:57.167 --> 31:58.333
♪ ♪

31:58.458 --> 32:00.916
My early days
with the Bee Gees

32:01.000 --> 32:03.791
were, for me, thrilling,

32:03.875 --> 32:06.375
even though I can understand
why it wasn't for them,

32:06.458 --> 32:08.958
'cause they weren't
necessarily selling out.

32:09.041 --> 32:11.624
[solemn music]

32:11.708 --> 32:12.916
- When we were broken up,

32:13.000 --> 32:15.958
the world changed radically
very quickly.

32:16.041 --> 32:17.749
And that was the beginning
of the period

32:17.833 --> 32:20.583
when there was just
no interest in us at all.

32:20.666 --> 32:22.292
- Remember, we were on tour.

32:22.375 --> 32:23.875
They'd try to keep Robin

32:23.958 --> 32:25.708
from looking out
into the audience,

32:25.791 --> 32:27.916
in case it was only half full.

32:28.000 --> 32:30.541
- When we got back home,
I turned to more drinking.

32:30.624 --> 32:33.583
I'd go to the pubs.
The police knew my car.

32:33.666 --> 32:36.583
I was becoming the town drunk.

32:36.666 --> 32:38.624
I mean, I think I had
about 2 grand in the bank

32:38.708 --> 32:40.833
and lived next order
to a fish and chips shop.

32:40.916 --> 32:42.916
- So by '74,

32:43.000 --> 32:46.292
we didn't think there was
gonna be much of a future.

32:46.375 --> 32:48.958
When you become famous,
you think everyone loves you

32:49.041 --> 32:50.250
and they're gonna love you
forever,

32:50.333 --> 32:51.624
and it's not true.

32:51.708 --> 32:53.791
["Marley Purt Drive"]

32:53.875 --> 32:55.624
[bluesy rock ballad]

32:55.708 --> 32:57.292
- All of a sudden now,
we had to work the clubs

32:57.375 --> 32:59.208
at the north of England
to pay the taxman,

32:59.292 --> 33:01.083
so we had
the Sheffield Fiesta,

33:01.167 --> 33:02.458
the Golden Garter
in Manchester,

33:02.541 --> 33:04.292
Batley Variety Club,

33:04.375 --> 33:06.083
great clubs of our time.

33:06.167 --> 33:07.749
- The Batley thing,

33:07.833 --> 33:10.125
it's where all the has-beens
went to play,

33:10.208 --> 33:11.624
and not saying
that they were has-beens,

33:11.708 --> 33:14.292
but it was like, "Oh, God,
not Batley," you know?

33:14.375 --> 33:16.333
- ♪ Sunday morning, woke up ♪

33:16.417 --> 33:19.375
- I was a waitress
at the Batley Variety Club.

33:19.458 --> 33:23.499
I really wasn't a fan
of the Bee Gees.

33:23.583 --> 33:25.708
The only thing I knew
about them was,

33:25.791 --> 33:26.791
you know, Maurice was mar--

33:26.875 --> 33:29.541
well, he was going through
a divorce with Lulu.

33:29.624 --> 33:33.041
- Yvonne came in,
and I saw her eyes.

33:33.125 --> 33:34.292
I don't know
about the rest of her.

33:34.375 --> 33:36.000
I just saw her eyes.

33:36.083 --> 33:39.000
And I said,
"I'm gonna marry her."

33:39.083 --> 33:41.583
And I knew
I was gonna marry her.

33:41.666 --> 33:43.125
- He was so cute.

33:43.208 --> 33:45.833
His personality was amazing.

33:45.916 --> 33:47.624
- Maurice had
this childlike quality,

33:47.708 --> 33:50.333
which is something
very special in men.

33:50.417 --> 33:53.708
- He loved dressing up
in police uniforms.

33:53.791 --> 33:55.875
Wherever we went on tour,

33:55.958 --> 33:57.708
they'd give him a hat,
give him a badge.

33:57.791 --> 33:58.791
- Is that his wallet?
- It's a badge.

33:58.875 --> 34:00.333
- Whoa!
[laughter]

34:00.417 --> 34:02.666
What was that?
- I'm not showing you now.

34:02.749 --> 34:04.041
- People loved him.

34:04.125 --> 34:05.875
He had the best smile ever.

34:05.958 --> 34:09.375
- I remember him teaching me
the showbiz smile,

34:09.458 --> 34:10.875
and he said,
"Well, the trick is,

34:10.958 --> 34:13.250
"you don't move your eyes

34:13.333 --> 34:15.583
and you just go like this."

34:15.666 --> 34:17.375
[laughs]

34:17.458 --> 34:19.000
And I'll be honest with you,

34:19.083 --> 34:22.208
I think Maurice was the glue
that held it all together.

34:22.292 --> 34:24.000
- Oh, I'm Mr. Fix-It.

34:24.083 --> 34:27.083
Either some discrepancy
between Barry and Robin,

34:27.167 --> 34:28.916
or if we're gonna make
a decision about something,

34:29.000 --> 34:30.375
"Well, what does
Maurice think?"

34:30.458 --> 34:33.708
But most of the time,
I'm like my mum.

34:33.791 --> 34:34.916
I'm the peacemaker.

34:35.000 --> 34:36.708
- You know,
if they'd not been brothers,

34:36.791 --> 34:38.875
they would not be together.

34:38.958 --> 34:41.250
No doubt in my mind.

34:41.333 --> 34:44.375
♪ ♪

34:44.458 --> 34:46.041
[soft music]

34:46.125 --> 34:48.250
- I met the Gibbs
when they were on a bit of a--

34:48.333 --> 34:50.125
shall we say, a downturn
in their career.

34:50.208 --> 34:51.624
Robert Stigwood made me,

34:51.708 --> 34:53.624
unaccountably,
the head of his record label.

34:53.708 --> 34:55.916
I was only 21 years old.

34:56.000 --> 34:57.417
I truly believed
it was because I was

34:57.499 --> 34:59.791
the only guy in the room
that I got the job.

34:59.875 --> 35:00.916
It was odd to me
because I thought,

35:01.000 --> 35:02.041
"If they can write those songs,

35:02.125 --> 35:03.791
how come they can't
be consistent?"

35:03.875 --> 35:05.083
If you got the ability
to write

35:05.167 --> 35:06.250
"How Can You Mend
a Broken Heart?"

35:06.333 --> 35:07.541
and "To Love Somebody,"

35:07.624 --> 35:09.583
where does that talent go?

35:09.666 --> 35:13.208
- I mean, there was two albums
in a row that were dismal.

35:13.292 --> 35:15.292
- Ahmet Ertegun
said to Robert,

35:15.375 --> 35:17.250
"You know,
maybe their time has gone,"

35:17.333 --> 35:18.749
'cause it was Atlantic
who were paying

35:18.833 --> 35:19.958
for these recordings,

35:20.041 --> 35:22.250
and Robert wouldn't hear of it,
of course.

35:22.333 --> 35:24.125
He would never let
the Bee Gees go.

35:24.208 --> 35:27.833
- There was this thing
about Stigwood--[laughs]

35:27.916 --> 35:31.417
Stigwood and his loyalties.

35:31.499 --> 35:33.666
I had a kind
of deep-seated resentment

35:33.749 --> 35:37.458
about the fact that,
you know, they were still

35:37.541 --> 35:38.499
his favorite.

35:38.583 --> 35:40.417
[Eric Clapton's
"Motherless Children"]

35:40.499 --> 35:42.333
[rollicking guitar music]

35:42.417 --> 35:44.833
I had come
out of a long period

35:44.916 --> 35:46.624
of addiction and alcoholism,

35:46.708 --> 35:49.583
and I went into
the sort of recovery period.

35:49.666 --> 35:51.167
♪ ♪

35:51.250 --> 35:54.292
All these musical ambitions
came to the surface,

35:54.375 --> 35:57.666
so I went to Miami to record.

35:57.749 --> 36:00.875
♪ ♪

36:00.958 --> 36:02.125
- We had a conversation
with Eric

36:02.208 --> 36:03.958
about making a comeback.

36:04.041 --> 36:05.167
Eric said, "Well,
I've just made this album

36:05.250 --> 36:07.749
"called '461 Ocean Boulevard'
in Miami.

36:07.833 --> 36:09.333
"Why don't you guys
make an album in America

36:09.417 --> 36:11.499
"instead of always
making an album in England,

36:11.583 --> 36:13.417
"and maybe the change
of environment

36:13.499 --> 36:15.666
will do something for you?"

36:15.749 --> 36:18.041
- The studio there
was unbelievable,

36:18.125 --> 36:21.666
and I think that's what

36:21.749 --> 36:23.833
the suggestion was about,
really.

36:23.916 --> 36:27.833
I thought those guys
were actually an R&B band

36:27.916 --> 36:30.541
that hadn't really
worked that out yet.

36:30.624 --> 36:32.833
And I thought,
"Man, this would be so good

36:32.916 --> 36:36.000
if they could pick up
on what's going on in America."

36:36.083 --> 36:39.624
- I do know that they had
to change something.

36:39.708 --> 36:40.833
That's when the whole idea

36:40.916 --> 36:43.958
of actually being
more of a band together

36:44.041 --> 36:45.125
rather than, you know,

36:45.208 --> 36:47.499
musicians and orchestras
and all that stuff.

36:47.583 --> 36:49.292
["Mr. Natural"]

36:49.375 --> 36:51.375
- Alan Kendall,
who was a friend of mine,

36:51.458 --> 36:54.624
said, "The Bee Gees
are looking for a drummer.

36:54.708 --> 36:56.916
You know, are you interested?"

36:57.000 --> 36:59.708
And I went, "Yes."
[laughs]

36:59.791 --> 37:02.624
"I think I'm interested.
Yeah. I am interested."

37:02.708 --> 37:05.208
- We needed to get
more energized

37:05.292 --> 37:06.708
and don't rely so much

37:06.791 --> 37:09.083
on the ballads
that we had been doing.

37:09.167 --> 37:12.041
- We wanted to be a band
so bad,

37:12.125 --> 37:14.041
and that was basically
the birth of it.

37:14.125 --> 37:16.875
- We had a great bass player,
Maurice.

37:16.958 --> 37:19.041
We had a great guitar player,
Alan.

37:19.125 --> 37:20.541
So really,
the only thing we needed

37:20.624 --> 37:22.375
was a keyboard player,

37:22.458 --> 37:24.375
and I thought, "Blue."

37:24.458 --> 37:27.375
[lively piano solo]

37:27.458 --> 37:30.916
♪ ♪

37:31.000 --> 37:32.708
- Dennis called and said,

37:32.791 --> 37:34.375
"Look, you know,
I'm putting a band together

37:34.458 --> 37:35.624
"with the Bee Gees,

37:35.708 --> 37:39.167
"and I've spoken to Barry,
and everybody's in agreement.

37:39.250 --> 37:40.916
Are you interested?"

37:41.000 --> 37:42.749
I said, "No. No.

37:42.833 --> 37:45.916
I'm having great fun.
I'm in a rock and roll band."

37:46.000 --> 37:47.708
Queen was our support act.

37:47.791 --> 37:50.749
I'm touring America and living
the rock and roll life.

37:50.833 --> 37:53.958
all: ♪ You don't get me,
I'm part of the union ♪

37:54.041 --> 37:57.875
♪ You don't get me,
I'm part of the union ♪

37:57.958 --> 38:01.041
- We'd grown up together
playing in bands in Cardiff.

38:01.125 --> 38:02.417
I said,
"We've known each other

38:02.499 --> 38:03.541
for a long time, right?"

38:03.624 --> 38:06.333
He said,
"Den, don't do this to me."

38:06.417 --> 38:08.417
And I said,
"I am doing it to you."

38:08.499 --> 38:10.541
I said, "Just do me one favor:

38:10.624 --> 38:12.417
"meet Barry.

38:12.499 --> 38:15.791
"And after you've met Barry,
if you don't wanna do it,

38:15.875 --> 38:17.624
I'll leave you alone."

38:17.708 --> 38:19.125
["Voices"]

38:19.208 --> 38:21.292
- Maurice and I had moved
to the Isle of Man,

38:21.375 --> 38:22.958
which is where we were born.

38:23.041 --> 38:25.916
Blue was the guy who was gonna
come to the Isle of Man

38:26.000 --> 38:28.167
and audition for us on piano.

38:28.250 --> 38:32.791
- ♪ If I were you
and you were me ♪

38:32.875 --> 38:34.583
- We were staying
in Barry's house,

38:34.666 --> 38:37.624
and it was Linda,
and then Maurice came over

38:37.708 --> 38:40.292
and Huey, the father.

38:40.375 --> 38:43.000
Instantly, you feel
comfortable with them.

38:43.083 --> 38:45.417
- They started talking
about synthesizers

38:45.499 --> 38:47.916
and Moogs,

38:48.000 --> 38:49.749
and Blue had them all.

38:49.833 --> 38:51.583
- There's the Sunday evening
I was leaving,

38:51.666 --> 38:55.083
and Huey said, "Hey,
we haven't heard you play."

38:55.167 --> 38:56.167
[laughs]

38:56.250 --> 38:58.833
- But my piano was so bad

38:58.916 --> 39:02.000
that he played something
and it just sounded awful.

39:02.083 --> 39:04.624
- It was just, like,
totally embarrassing.

39:04.708 --> 39:07.000
- I said, "Sounds fine
to me, man.

39:07.083 --> 39:08.292
Let's do it," you know?

39:08.375 --> 39:10.000
- Barry offered him the job.

39:10.083 --> 39:12.208
- I'd always loved the music,

39:12.292 --> 39:14.666
but the first time
you ever hear the Bee Gees

39:14.749 --> 39:16.499
just when they're in a room
like this,

39:16.583 --> 39:18.167
you know, it's just magic.

39:18.250 --> 39:20.833
I think that's
what won me over with them.

39:20.916 --> 39:22.083
I said yes,

39:22.167 --> 39:25.167
and January the 1st, we left.

39:25.250 --> 39:27.167
all: ♪ Doo-doo-doo,
doo-doo-doo ♪

39:27.250 --> 39:30.791
♪ Doo-dee-doo, dah, day ♪

39:35.417 --> 39:38.791
["Wind of Change"]

39:38.875 --> 39:41.749
[upbeat R&B music]

39:41.833 --> 39:48.833
♪ ♪

39:51.583 --> 39:53.250
- Miami's a gateway city,

39:53.333 --> 39:56.041
but in those days,
it was kind of sleepy.

39:56.125 --> 39:59.333
You know, a little off
the beaten path.

39:59.417 --> 40:01.916
But in the winter,
that was the place to be,

40:02.000 --> 40:04.875
so Atlantic Records
would always book their acts

40:04.958 --> 40:06.541
down at Criteria.

40:06.624 --> 40:08.583
- ♪ And the lights ♪

40:08.666 --> 40:10.250
- I was about
the number three engineer

40:10.333 --> 40:11.375
at the studio.

40:11.458 --> 40:12.499
I worked my way up,

40:12.583 --> 40:14.833
and I was at that point
in my career

40:14.916 --> 40:17.167
where I was ready for anything.

40:17.250 --> 40:18.875
- ♪ Get on up ♪

40:18.958 --> 40:20.749
♪ Look around ♪

40:20.833 --> 40:24.749
♪ Can't you feel
the wind of change? ♪

40:24.833 --> 40:26.791
- When we got to Miami,
all of a sudden, sunshine,

40:26.875 --> 40:28.708
and, oh, you know?

40:28.791 --> 40:30.458
This is paradise.

40:30.541 --> 40:31.541
- We'd come from England,

40:31.624 --> 40:34.083
and so there was nothing
sleepy about America.

40:34.167 --> 40:36.250
- Put them in the same house
I'd rented for Eric Clapton,

40:36.333 --> 40:38.417
461 Ocean Boulevard.

40:38.499 --> 40:39.958
- I think the first thing
all of us did was

40:40.041 --> 40:41.958
take pictures against
that palm tree, you know,

40:42.041 --> 40:44.250
doing the Eric Clapton pose.

40:44.333 --> 40:47.083
- ♪ We need a god down here ♪

40:47.167 --> 40:48.541
- Being in that house
together,

40:48.624 --> 40:50.292
you know, we were creative,

40:50.375 --> 40:51.292
and we were a family.

40:51.375 --> 40:53.083
I mean, I felt like that.

40:53.167 --> 40:55.041
- It did make us close.

40:55.125 --> 40:58.041
I mean, you had to be.
And we'd all watch TV at night.

40:58.125 --> 41:00.083
The chemistry
was very exciting.

41:00.167 --> 41:01.292
- When you got up
in the morning,

41:01.375 --> 41:02.958
you went to breakfast;
you had a cup of tea.

41:03.041 --> 41:05.833
It was all very relaxed.

41:05.916 --> 41:11.167
- ♪ Can't you see
the wind of change? ♪

41:11.250 --> 41:13.624
- It was strange, considering
the amount of pressure

41:13.708 --> 41:16.083
that was really on the Bee Gees
at that time.

41:16.167 --> 41:17.541
- They were about to drop us.

41:17.624 --> 41:19.417
We had to adopt a new sound.

41:19.499 --> 41:21.167
We had to adopt
a new attitude.

41:21.250 --> 41:23.624
- So the next step was,
we brought Arif Mardin in

41:23.708 --> 41:24.791
to produce them.

41:24.875 --> 41:26.333
[Aretha Franklin's
"Day Dreaming"]

41:26.417 --> 41:28.791
- ♪ Daydreaming
and I'm thinking of you ♪

41:28.875 --> 41:30.125
- We'd often work
with other people,

41:30.208 --> 41:31.499
but they weren't producers,

41:31.583 --> 41:34.000
and this man
was a literal producer.

41:34.083 --> 41:36.417
- They had expressed
how much they wanted to do

41:36.499 --> 41:38.250
American R&B kind of stuff,

41:38.333 --> 41:41.000
and Arif was, you know,
top of the heap for that.

41:41.083 --> 41:44.208
- Arif was so instrumental
in producing Black artists,

41:44.292 --> 41:45.666
and we wanted that input.

41:45.749 --> 41:51.292
- ♪ It turns me right on
when I hear him say ♪

41:51.375 --> 41:54.333
- We actually did an album
with Arif before that,

41:54.417 --> 41:57.000
but Arif said, "We've gotta go
more into R&B,"

41:57.083 --> 41:58.791
and we started
working together

41:58.875 --> 42:02.083
right here in Miami,
down at Criteria.

42:03.083 --> 42:05.000
- Well, I was in Studio B,

42:05.083 --> 42:06.875
and Arif says to me,

42:06.958 --> 42:09.875
"Carl, have I got a group
for you."

42:09.958 --> 42:12.666
And of course, everybody knew
the Bee Gees.

42:12.749 --> 42:14.833
It was a surprise
out of nowhere.

42:14.916 --> 42:16.000
I was excited.

42:16.083 --> 42:17.250
You know,
they sing like angels.

42:17.333 --> 42:20.125
And they were as excited
as I was.

42:20.208 --> 42:22.333
And Arif was right in there
with them.

42:22.417 --> 42:23.499
- He said, "Look,

42:23.583 --> 42:25.916
"if you're ever going
to break out brand-new,

42:26.000 --> 42:27.083
"you gotta start now.

42:27.167 --> 42:28.417
"You gotta shock the pants
off these people

42:28.499 --> 42:29.708
who don't believe in you."

42:29.791 --> 42:32.541
- Robert came and saw us
when we were making the album,

42:32.624 --> 42:35.499
sat down with us on the beach,
and said, "Right.

42:35.583 --> 42:37.250
"We're gonna start
from scratch.

42:37.333 --> 42:38.791
"This is gonna be it.

42:38.875 --> 42:40.083
Let's make it big."

42:40.167 --> 42:42.041
- ♪ Whoa ♪

42:42.125 --> 42:44.250
- If you said to me or anyone,

42:44.333 --> 42:46.875
"Just go and write a hit song
right now,"

42:46.958 --> 42:48.708
they would be able to craft
something good,

42:48.791 --> 42:51.000
but it would probably be
missing this magic

42:51.083 --> 42:53.208
that, if you work in music
long enough,

42:53.292 --> 42:56.791
you understand
is running everything.

42:56.875 --> 42:59.708
Like surfers with waves.
Surfers don't make the waves.

42:59.791 --> 43:01.833
Fishermen don't make the fish.

43:01.916 --> 43:03.333
Songwriters don't really
write songs.

43:03.417 --> 43:04.749
You receive songs.

43:04.833 --> 43:06.417
["Jive Talkin'"]

43:06.499 --> 43:08.916
- Driving backwards
and forwards to Criteria,

43:09.000 --> 43:11.417
this clickity-click thing
was going on in this bridge

43:11.499 --> 43:13.292
every time we crossed over it.

43:13.375 --> 43:14.708
And in my head,
it sounded like,

43:14.791 --> 43:15.749
"ch, ch-ch, ch-ch."

43:15.833 --> 43:19.125
[rhythmic clacking]

43:19.208 --> 43:20.708
And it was gone.

43:20.791 --> 43:23.749
And eventually, I started
singing to it in my head.

43:23.833 --> 43:26.666
♪ Just your jive talkin' ♪

43:26.749 --> 43:28.083
- I remember going
to the studio.

43:28.167 --> 43:30.624
Barry said, "Can you do
chicken picking, Alan?"

43:30.708 --> 43:33.583
I didn't really know
what it was.

43:33.666 --> 43:35.708
So I just played this one note
and muted it.

43:35.791 --> 43:37.083
Thought it sounded
like a chicken.

43:37.167 --> 43:39.875
[mimicking guitar lick]

43:39.958 --> 43:41.250
And mixed
with Barry's rhythm part,

43:41.333 --> 43:43.208
it really worked, you know?

43:43.292 --> 43:45.916
- ♪ It's just
your jive talkin' ♪

43:46.000 --> 43:48.333
♪ You're telling me lies,
yeah ♪

43:48.417 --> 43:50.250
♪ Jive talkin' ♪

43:50.333 --> 43:52.624
♪ You wear a disguise ♪

43:52.708 --> 43:54.417
♪ Jive talkin' ♪

43:54.499 --> 43:56.958
♪ So misunderstood, yeah ♪

43:57.041 --> 43:58.791
♪ Jive talkin' ♪

43:58.875 --> 44:01.000
♪ You really no good ♪

44:01.083 --> 44:02.125
- At that time, you know,

44:02.208 --> 44:04.499
a handful of R&B artists
were using synthesizers,

44:04.583 --> 44:08.125
so we went into this field

44:08.208 --> 44:10.499
pioneering, in a way.

44:10.583 --> 44:13.499
[synth solo]

44:13.583 --> 44:14.666
♪ ♪

44:14.749 --> 44:18.499
- Music is this huge energy
flying around everywhere,

44:18.583 --> 44:20.791
and if you're lucky,
you get little slices of it

44:20.875 --> 44:21.916
that turn into songs.

44:22.000 --> 44:23.083
- There is a sort of--

44:23.167 --> 44:25.167
- Like a radio transmitter.
- It's exactly like that.

44:25.250 --> 44:26.791
It's almost as if
somebody's already written

44:26.875 --> 44:28.916
the songs in the air
and they're giving them to us.

44:29.000 --> 44:32.333
♪ Leaving me looking
like a dumbstruck fool ♪

44:32.417 --> 44:34.791
♪ With all your jive talkin' ♪

44:34.875 --> 44:35.833
♪ You're telling me lies ♪

44:35.916 --> 44:37.041
- It was Robert
who really pressed

44:37.125 --> 44:39.333
for "Jive Talkin'" to come out
as the first single,

44:39.417 --> 44:41.875
because it was something
totally unexpected from us.

44:41.958 --> 44:43.125
- We sent the record out

44:43.208 --> 44:44.666
but without naming
the Bee Gees on it,

44:44.749 --> 44:48.167
because by then,
their stock had fallen so low

44:48.250 --> 44:49.875
with radio stations
in America,

44:49.958 --> 44:52.167
and within hours

44:52.250 --> 44:53.624
of the record landing
at all the radio stations,

44:53.708 --> 44:55.000
they were calling in, saying,
"Who is this?

44:55.083 --> 44:56.458
This is amazing."

44:56.541 --> 44:59.292
[radio tuning]

44:59.375 --> 45:01.833
- The British group who move
into number one this week

45:01.916 --> 45:02.833
hit number one

45:02.916 --> 45:05.292
exactly four years ago
to the week.

45:05.375 --> 45:06.375
[drumroll]

45:06.458 --> 45:09.167
The brand-new number one song
in the USA,

45:09.250 --> 45:12.041
the Bee Gees
and "Jive Talkin'."

45:12.125 --> 45:16.791
♪ ♪

45:16.875 --> 45:18.375
- When "Jive Talkin'"
came out,

45:18.458 --> 45:19.624
everybody went, "Who?

45:19.708 --> 45:21.541
"The Bee Gees?
'Broken Heart' Bee Gees?

45:21.624 --> 45:22.916
Are you kidding?"

45:23.000 --> 45:24.541
- Something different
was happening,

45:24.624 --> 45:26.167
and the brothers felt it too.

45:26.250 --> 45:27.417
Miami, Miami Beach,

45:27.499 --> 45:29.499
that whole vibe
turned them on.

45:29.583 --> 45:31.875
- I just fell in love
with the atmosphere here.

45:31.958 --> 45:34.749
It reminded me so much
of growing up in Australia.

45:35.624 --> 45:36.833
- That's great, Rob.

45:36.916 --> 45:38.875
- And from "Jive Talkin'"
onwards,

45:38.958 --> 45:40.875
we kicked it up.

45:40.958 --> 45:43.167
- The songwriting was
just very unique.

45:43.250 --> 45:44.333
Nothing like it.

45:44.417 --> 45:45.708
They would write on the spot,

45:45.791 --> 45:47.875
and they would bounce
off each other.

45:47.958 --> 45:50.417
- Okay, you let us know
when you're ready.

45:50.499 --> 45:52.208
- "Nights on Broadway"
was one of those.

45:52.292 --> 45:54.292
The guys had been to New York,
and they go, "Oh, this is--

45:54.375 --> 45:56.250
we gotta write
a New York kind of song."

45:56.333 --> 45:57.833
- Here we go.
Take ten.

45:57.916 --> 45:59.916
- They just did it naturally
in the studio,

46:00.000 --> 46:01.417
and everybody chipped in.

46:01.499 --> 46:02.458
- Three, four.

46:02.541 --> 46:05.916
[funky music]

46:06.000 --> 46:08.041
♪ ♪

46:08.125 --> 46:11.417
- ♪ Well, here we are ♪

46:11.499 --> 46:13.541
♪ In a room
full of strangers ♪

46:13.624 --> 46:15.583
Ahmet Ertegun came to Miami.

46:15.666 --> 46:18.083
He was there when we were
cutting "Nights on Broadway."

46:18.167 --> 46:20.458
At the time,
it was "Lights on Broadway."

46:20.541 --> 46:22.749
♪ Blaming it all ♪

46:22.833 --> 46:24.875
♪ On the lights on Broadway ♪

46:24.958 --> 46:25.875
[music distorts]

46:25.958 --> 46:28.458
And Ahmet went, "No."
[laughs]

46:28.541 --> 46:30.791
He said, "You know,
you've got to get more adult

46:30.875 --> 46:32.375
about the song."

46:32.458 --> 46:34.749
So "Lights on Broadway"
became "Nights on Broadway."

46:34.833 --> 46:38.624
- ♪ Well, I had to follow you ♪

46:38.708 --> 46:40.250
♪ ♪

46:40.333 --> 46:43.916
both: ♪ Though you did not
want me to ♪

46:44.000 --> 46:46.000
♪ ♪

46:46.083 --> 46:49.083
all: ♪ But that won't stop
my loving you ♪

46:49.167 --> 46:50.791
♪ ♪

46:50.875 --> 46:54.541
♪ I can't stay away ♪

46:54.624 --> 46:57.125
♪ Blaming it all ♪

46:57.208 --> 47:00.125
♪ On the nights on Broadway ♪

47:00.208 --> 47:02.458
♪ Singing them love songs ♪

47:02.541 --> 47:04.708
♪ Singing them
"straight to the heart" songs ♪

47:04.791 --> 47:06.250
- We were completing
"Nights on Broadway."

47:06.333 --> 47:08.167
We'd just done
most of the vocal tracks.

47:08.250 --> 47:09.499
Usually, you know,
at the end, you know,

47:09.583 --> 47:11.167
you have some ad-libs
or some kind of thing

47:11.250 --> 47:12.666
to take us away
from the original melody

47:12.749 --> 47:13.958
and have some fun.

47:14.041 --> 47:15.666
- Arif suggested to the band,

47:15.749 --> 47:18.167
"Hey, you know, we really need
some kind of background parts

47:18.250 --> 47:21.375
that come in and express
the meaning of the song."

47:21.458 --> 47:23.833
- He was looking for one of us
to scream,

47:23.916 --> 47:25.875
in tune, if possible.

47:25.958 --> 47:28.208
I said, "I'll go out
and give it a shot."

47:28.292 --> 47:30.624
- Are we almost ready?
Let's do it.

47:30.708 --> 47:32.000
- So he went out there
and he did

47:32.083 --> 47:35.666
the "blaming it alls."

47:35.749 --> 47:36.916
- [falsetto]
♪ Blame it all ♪

47:37.000 --> 47:38.458
- ♪ On the nights
on Broadway ♪

47:38.541 --> 47:41.000
- ♪ Blame it on the nights
on Broadway ♪

47:41.083 --> 47:42.875
- Everybody in the control room
woke up,

47:42.958 --> 47:45.666
and it was like,
"Oh, this is a new sound."

47:45.749 --> 47:46.791
- ♪ Blame it all ♪

47:46.875 --> 47:48.458
- ♪ On the nights
on Broadway ♪

47:48.541 --> 47:49.916
- ♪ Blame it on the nights
on Broadway ♪

47:50.000 --> 47:51.333
I was thinking,
"My God, I don't--

47:51.417 --> 47:52.458
"where is this coming from?

47:52.541 --> 47:53.499
I can do this."

47:53.583 --> 47:55.958
My whole life, I didn't know
I could do this.

47:56.041 --> 47:57.333
- Everybody's giving me credit.

47:57.458 --> 47:59.583
No, he was singing it.
I said, "Keep on doing it."

47:59.666 --> 48:01.666
- ♪ Blame it on the nights
on Broadway ♪

48:01.749 --> 48:03.417
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

48:03.499 --> 48:05.083
♪ Ah ♪

48:05.167 --> 48:07.167
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

48:07.250 --> 48:09.083
- Arif brought it out of us,
all that.

48:09.167 --> 48:10.708
I mean, we weren't the first
to sing falsetto.

48:10.791 --> 48:14.541
[The Stylistics' "Can't Give
You Anything (But My Love)"]

48:14.624 --> 48:15.708
We loved the Stylistics.

48:15.791 --> 48:18.708
We loved the Spinners,
the Delfonics.

48:18.791 --> 48:21.333
They were all
falsetto lead singers.

48:21.417 --> 48:24.749
- ♪ If I had money,
I'd go out ♪

48:24.833 --> 48:29.208
♪ Buy you furs,
dress you like a queen ♪

48:29.292 --> 48:31.250
- There's something to be said
about all music

48:31.333 --> 48:33.541
is that it doesn't happen
in a vacuum.

48:33.624 --> 48:37.208
The falsetto is very much
a Black tradition,

48:37.292 --> 48:38.541
but they've translated it

48:38.624 --> 48:42.624
into this interesting
interpretation of soul.

48:42.708 --> 48:44.458
But I guess
more importantly for me,

48:44.541 --> 48:45.458
it's emotional.

48:45.541 --> 48:50.916
- [falsetto]
♪ Ah ♪

48:51.000 --> 48:52.417
Because we were so excited
about this,

48:52.499 --> 48:54.791
we started writing songs
for this voice.

48:54.875 --> 48:57.250
- It created another dimension
of sound--

48:57.333 --> 48:59.417
that's what we thought--
you know, emotionally.

48:59.499 --> 49:02.875
It became another icon
of the Gibbs.

49:02.958 --> 49:05.417
Everybody knew,
when you heard that falsetto,

49:05.499 --> 49:07.041
that's the Bee Gees.

49:07.125 --> 49:09.250
both: ♪ Be tender ♪

49:09.333 --> 49:12.208
♪ With my love ♪

49:12.292 --> 49:16.417
♪ You know how easy it is
to hurt me ♪

49:16.499 --> 49:17.749
- When we sing songs like...

49:17.833 --> 49:21.624
♪ You know how easy it is
to hurt me ♪

49:21.708 --> 49:23.499
It's Barry and Robin
singing in unison.

49:23.583 --> 49:27.000
But they mesh together so well
that it sounds like one voice.

49:27.083 --> 49:30.125
But it's a different voice
from them separately.

49:30.208 --> 49:31.958
- ♪ With my love ♪

49:32.041 --> 49:36.624
both: ♪ You know
how easy it is to hurt me ♪

49:36.708 --> 49:38.791
♪ Fanny, be tender ♪

49:38.875 --> 49:40.916
- It's delivered
with such delicacy,

49:41.000 --> 49:45.624
and the message in the lyrics

49:45.708 --> 49:49.624
was what guys should say,
didn't say, couldn't say,

49:49.708 --> 49:50.791
for whatever reasons.

49:50.875 --> 49:52.624
It's the kind of music
you might've bought

49:52.708 --> 49:53.749
and given to your girlfriend.

49:53.833 --> 49:55.000
[laughs]

49:55.083 --> 49:57.333
But that's what was special
about them.

49:57.417 --> 50:00.958
both: [vocalizing]

50:01.041 --> 50:03.333
♪ Fanny, be tender ♪

50:03.417 --> 50:04.541
♪ With my love ♪

50:04.624 --> 50:07.167
- "Main Course" became
a turning point for us.

50:07.250 --> 50:08.958
Dennis Bryon on drums

50:09.041 --> 50:12.000
and Blue Weaver
and Alan Kendall,

50:12.083 --> 50:13.708
that became our band.

50:13.791 --> 50:15.666
♪ With my love ♪

50:15.749 --> 50:18.167
- ♪ 'Cause it's all
that I've got ♪

50:18.250 --> 50:21.125
♪ And my love
won't desert me ♪

50:21.208 --> 50:23.292
both: ♪ Be tender
with my love ♪

50:23.375 --> 50:26.708
- One of their best qualities
was adaptability.

50:26.791 --> 50:30.833
In many ways,
they were chameleons of pop.

50:30.916 --> 50:32.333
- The way they changed

50:32.417 --> 50:34.458
and the groove
they got into there

50:34.541 --> 50:36.499
was so profound.

50:36.583 --> 50:40.000
If that was something
that was initiated by me,

50:40.083 --> 50:41.083
I can't think of any--

50:41.167 --> 50:43.833
one of the great things
I've done in my life.

50:43.916 --> 50:45.583
I'll take full credit.

50:45.666 --> 50:47.208
[laughs]

50:47.292 --> 50:50.292
[waves crashing]

50:54.167 --> 50:57.583
- We're getting ready
to record the next album,

50:57.666 --> 50:58.666
and we get this phone call

50:58.749 --> 51:01.666
that Arif can't be involved
in this album.

51:01.749 --> 51:04.000
[tense music]

51:04.083 --> 51:06.375
Robert chose to take

51:06.458 --> 51:08.417
the organization away
from Atlantic Records

51:08.499 --> 51:11.041
and go private.

51:11.125 --> 51:13.333
Atlantic, who were not happy
about that, said,

51:13.417 --> 51:14.708
"Well, you're not using
Arif anymore

51:14.791 --> 51:16.375
as a house producer."

51:16.458 --> 51:18.041
I said,
"What about the next album?"

51:18.125 --> 51:19.583
Arif--you know, I said,

51:19.666 --> 51:21.916
"Who do you think can continue
where you left off?"

51:22.000 --> 51:23.916
♪ ♪

51:24.000 --> 51:25.749
- I got a call from Barry,

51:25.833 --> 51:27.791
and he said,
"I want my studio time back

51:27.875 --> 51:28.958
and I wanna work with you."

51:29.041 --> 51:31.958
[scratchy music playing]

51:32.041 --> 51:33.250
♪ ♪

51:33.333 --> 51:35.000
And I'm in the control room.

51:35.083 --> 51:36.708
I said to Dennis, the drummer,
I says, you know,

51:36.791 --> 51:37.875
"That pattern you're playing
right now

51:37.958 --> 51:39.583
is just a little too busy."

51:39.666 --> 51:41.749
♪ ♪

51:41.833 --> 51:43.417
He said,
"Well, what do you mean?"

51:43.499 --> 51:45.458
I said, "I can't get
into specifics

51:45.541 --> 51:47.250
about the note values."

51:47.333 --> 51:50.250
I didn't have a technical term
for the open and closed hi-hat

51:50.333 --> 51:51.583
or any of that stuff.

51:51.666 --> 51:55.250
So apparently, you know,
I needed a communicator.

51:55.333 --> 51:58.208
[funky groove]

51:58.292 --> 51:59.666
- I was working
as an independent producer

51:59.749 --> 52:01.958
on some pub band in London.

52:02.041 --> 52:04.417
Carl called and he said,
"What are you doing?"

52:04.499 --> 52:05.916
And I said,
"Well, I just finished the mix.

52:06.000 --> 52:06.958
I'm on a plane tomorrow."

52:07.041 --> 52:08.916
- Albhy went
to Berklee School of Music

52:09.000 --> 52:09.958
in New England,

52:10.041 --> 52:12.458
and he was
one of my best friends.

52:12.541 --> 52:14.749
And he says, "I'll be
on the next flight to Florida."

52:14.833 --> 52:17.208
- ♪ Baby, keep it coming ♪

52:17.292 --> 52:19.958
- I got off the plane.
I went straight to the studio.

52:20.041 --> 52:21.125
I walked in.

52:21.208 --> 52:23.167
They were working
on "You Should Be Dancing."

52:23.250 --> 52:24.292
They came in the control room,

52:24.375 --> 52:25.916
and Barry said,
"What did you think?"

52:26.000 --> 52:27.458
And I said,
"Well, I just got in,

52:27.541 --> 52:29.624
but sounds awfully good."

52:29.708 --> 52:32.125
We seemed to hit it off,
so I came back the next day.

52:32.208 --> 52:34.292
- Now, what you have
to remember at the time,

52:34.375 --> 52:35.499
Albhy was a hippie.

52:35.583 --> 52:37.125
I mean, he was just different.

52:37.208 --> 52:39.833
- ♪ I get nothing ♪

52:39.916 --> 52:42.125
- Albhy used to hang
around the studio,

52:42.208 --> 52:43.624
and I got on really well
with him.

52:43.708 --> 52:46.791
I found out he played
on "I Shot the Sheriff"

52:46.875 --> 52:47.958
with Eric.

52:48.041 --> 52:51.499
- Albhy had an inroad
into technology,

52:51.583 --> 52:52.749
and he had a great ear.

52:52.833 --> 52:55.624
- Everybody just seemed to be,
I think, relieved

52:55.708 --> 52:59.000
to have another ear
in the control room

52:59.083 --> 53:01.250
to hear what they were doing
as a whole.

53:01.333 --> 53:04.208
["Love So Right"]

53:04.292 --> 53:07.208
[mellow ballad]

53:07.292 --> 53:10.167
♪ ♪

53:10.250 --> 53:12.167
In the beginning, when I came,

53:12.250 --> 53:14.666
the three brothers
were clearly a unit.

53:14.749 --> 53:16.499
Each of them knew
the way their brothers sang

53:16.583 --> 53:18.041
and would be on the same mic

53:18.125 --> 53:19.833
and they would lean in
or lean out

53:19.916 --> 53:22.125
or complement
each other's voices.

53:22.208 --> 53:24.000
They were in perfect synchrony.

53:24.083 --> 53:27.833
all: ♪ How a love so right ♪

53:27.916 --> 53:31.875
♪ Can turn out to be
so wrong ♪

53:31.958 --> 53:34.499
- We found another sound.
We found a new sound.

53:34.583 --> 53:36.666
I came up
with a lot of new ideas

53:36.749 --> 53:38.333
to suit the falsetto.

53:38.417 --> 53:40.208
Everybody was saying
the same thing:

53:40.292 --> 53:42.541
"Do that falsetto again.
Do that falsetto again."

53:42.624 --> 53:45.041
And so that was fine for me.
I was having a ball.

53:45.125 --> 53:48.041
["You Should Be Dancing"]

53:48.125 --> 53:50.708
[upbeat disco music]

53:50.791 --> 53:54.375
- A lot of new music has been
coming out of Miami lately,

53:54.458 --> 53:56.541
enough so
that we've even heard mentioned

53:56.624 --> 53:59.041
the term "Miami Sound."

53:59.125 --> 54:00.208
♪ ♪

54:00.292 --> 54:03.916
- ♪ My baby moves
at midnight ♪

54:04.000 --> 54:06.708
♪ Goes right on
till the dawn ♪

54:06.791 --> 54:08.708
- This is actually
a really important period

54:08.791 --> 54:11.833
for musicianship and production
and songwriting

54:11.916 --> 54:13.791
that targets the dance floor.

54:13.875 --> 54:15.624
♪ ♪

54:15.708 --> 54:17.250
- ♪ What you doing
on your back? ♪

54:17.333 --> 54:18.583
- It's a different
emotional energy,

54:18.666 --> 54:21.083
which is about,
can you make the body move?

54:21.167 --> 54:22.958
Can you make the body happy?

54:23.041 --> 54:25.499
- ♪ You should be dancing ♪

54:25.583 --> 54:27.749
♪ Yeah ♪

54:27.833 --> 54:29.583
♪ Dancing, yeah ♪

54:29.666 --> 54:31.083
- And certain songs
sounded like

54:31.167 --> 54:34.791
the human embodiment
of a brass section.

54:34.875 --> 54:36.916
The same way
a horn just punches...

54:37.000 --> 54:38.250
- Yeah.

54:38.333 --> 54:39.958
- That's what Barry's voice
reminds me of.

54:40.041 --> 54:42.958
- ♪ Gives me power ♪

54:43.041 --> 54:45.624
♪ Goes right down to my blood ♪

54:45.708 --> 54:49.417
- I was always into arrangement
of instruments.

54:49.499 --> 54:50.708
"You Should Be Dancing,"

54:50.791 --> 54:54.208
their voices together
sound like trumpets to me.

54:54.292 --> 54:58.000
- ♪ You should be dancing,
yeah ♪

54:58.083 --> 54:59.624
- I am not high,
for the record.

54:59.708 --> 55:02.958
I just wanna--
[laughter]

55:03.041 --> 55:06.916
- [scatting to horn section]

55:07.000 --> 55:07.916
It was a discovery.

55:08.000 --> 55:09.916
We've discovered
a new audience.

55:10.000 --> 55:10.916
- At the clubs,

55:11.000 --> 55:13.499
"You Should Be Dancing"
exploded.

55:13.583 --> 55:15.666
Not just, "Oh, well,
I heard that record

55:15.749 --> 55:16.916
and I really liked it."

55:17.000 --> 55:21.417
It was three times a night
at any club that you went to.

55:21.499 --> 55:23.292
There was a whole industry

55:23.375 --> 55:26.208
that was built
around this clubbing thing.

55:26.292 --> 55:30.458
"Billboard" started a chart
that was dance music chart.

55:30.541 --> 55:34.499
This billion-dollar industry
was being built

55:34.583 --> 55:36.499
way before the Bee Gees.

55:36.583 --> 55:38.624
A lot of people don't realize

55:38.708 --> 55:42.708
disco started in the gay
and the Black community.

55:42.791 --> 55:44.167
People don't understand

55:44.250 --> 55:46.791
what it was like back then
for gay people.

55:46.875 --> 55:48.375
There was a law in New York

55:48.458 --> 55:51.833
that did not allow
people of the same sex

55:51.916 --> 55:53.333
to dance together

55:53.417 --> 55:57.000
in a place
that had a liquor license.

55:57.083 --> 55:59.041
And then the law changed,

55:59.125 --> 56:01.875
and that allowed me
to open my club.

56:01.958 --> 56:03.375
- ♪ Whoo-hoo ♪

56:03.458 --> 56:06.292
- A new era
of dance music started

56:06.375 --> 56:09.041
in the gay underground clubs.

56:09.125 --> 56:12.499
- [scatting to disco beat]

56:12.583 --> 56:13.666
[Don Downing's "Dream World"]

56:13.749 --> 56:18.333
- So the record industry wants
to name it,

56:18.458 --> 56:20.749
package it, sell it.

56:20.833 --> 56:23.541
That was the explosion

56:23.624 --> 56:26.000
of the disco sound.

56:26.083 --> 56:28.208
- ♪ Dream world ♪

56:28.292 --> 56:32.708
♪ ♪

56:32.791 --> 56:35.541
- We're down
at Criteria Sound Studios,

56:35.624 --> 56:37.875
and currently, it's the studio

56:37.958 --> 56:40.292
that's being used
by the Bee Gees.

56:40.375 --> 56:43.041
What particular thing
about the studio

56:43.125 --> 56:44.333
makes it so attractive?

56:44.417 --> 56:46.333
- It's cheap.
- It's cheap, yeah.

56:46.417 --> 56:50.208
- No.
Cheap it isn't, but--

56:50.292 --> 56:53.000
- But the actual atmosphere
of the place is very relaxing.

56:53.083 --> 56:54.583
We create better here
than we do anywhere else.

56:54.666 --> 56:55.708
- Yeah.

56:55.791 --> 56:57.208
- That's my story,
and I'm sticking to it.

56:57.292 --> 56:58.916
[laughter]

56:59.000 --> 57:02.375
[upbeat disco music]

57:02.458 --> 57:04.916
America was
the ultimate dream.

57:05.000 --> 57:07.250
As three kids, we said,

57:07.333 --> 57:09.250
"One day, we're gonna have
houses in America

57:09.333 --> 57:11.583
all next door to each other
with swimming pools."

57:11.666 --> 57:12.791
[laughs]

57:12.875 --> 57:14.125
And we thought,
"Oh, that'll be great."

57:14.208 --> 57:19.417
♪ ♪

57:19.499 --> 57:21.791
- It was a huge uprooting.

57:21.875 --> 57:23.458
♪ ♪

57:23.541 --> 57:25.541
It's a very large family,

57:25.624 --> 57:28.417
and it just kept getting
bigger and bigger over time.

57:28.499 --> 57:30.250
♪ ♪

57:30.333 --> 57:33.583
Mum and Dad came to Miami
as quickly as we did.

57:33.666 --> 57:35.749
I think they were probably
the happiest they'd ever been

57:35.833 --> 57:36.958
in their lives.

57:37.041 --> 57:40.375
And of course,
Andy came here with them.

57:42.541 --> 57:45.833
- Andy was a gift
out of left field.

57:45.916 --> 57:50.000
But I never knew he existed
until one day, he shows up

57:50.083 --> 57:52.958
fresh from Australia.

57:53.041 --> 57:55.083
- Andy was a great kid.

57:55.167 --> 57:57.458
He could do anything
he set his mind to.

57:57.541 --> 58:00.125
- Barry was Andy's idol.

58:00.208 --> 58:02.250
They were almost like twins.

58:02.333 --> 58:03.583
- We were very much alike.

58:03.666 --> 58:05.833
We looked alike.
We had the same birthmarks.

58:05.916 --> 58:07.624
I would say that we were
as much like twins

58:07.708 --> 58:09.624
as Maurice and Robin.

58:09.708 --> 58:11.583
- "Main Course"
and "Children of the World,"

58:11.666 --> 58:12.624
which followed that,

58:12.708 --> 58:13.749
they were, like,
triple platinum.

58:13.833 --> 58:16.624
I think he really wanted
to be a part of that.

58:16.708 --> 58:18.458
- They suggested
that I go to Australia,

58:18.541 --> 58:20.125
as my brothers first did
in 1958

58:20.208 --> 58:21.791
when I was only
five months old,

58:21.875 --> 58:25.000
and start working there
and get some records released.

58:25.083 --> 58:27.167
- Andy was very young then.

58:27.250 --> 58:29.125
He had his little band.

58:29.208 --> 58:30.708
- It was a process
of building him up,

58:30.791 --> 58:34.083
getting him to play live,
getting him to be an artist.

58:34.167 --> 58:35.499
- I was there for two years.

58:35.583 --> 58:36.833
Out of the blue,
a phone call came

58:36.916 --> 58:37.791
from my brother Barry

58:37.875 --> 58:39.541
and said,
"I wanna produce you,"

58:39.624 --> 58:41.375
and I think it was, like,
two weeks or something,

58:41.458 --> 58:44.499
I was in the studio
to do a new album in Miami.

58:44.583 --> 58:46.167
I didn't think I was ready.

58:46.250 --> 58:47.208
- The first few times

58:47.292 --> 58:49.375
on a real professional
studio microphone,

58:49.458 --> 58:51.499
Andy was, like, petrified,

58:51.583 --> 58:54.041
but, you know, Barry was there

58:54.125 --> 58:56.875
and guided him through
and helped him with lyrics.

58:56.958 --> 58:59.666
He was very receptive
to new ideas.

58:59.749 --> 59:02.791
[Andy Gibb's "I Just Want
to Be Your Everything"]

59:02.875 --> 59:05.083
And it didn't take him long,
you know,

59:05.167 --> 59:08.208
to find, like, you know,
another groove.

59:08.292 --> 59:11.167
[upbeat pop music playing]

59:11.250 --> 59:13.250
♪ ♪

59:13.333 --> 59:16.708
- ♪ For so long ♪

59:16.791 --> 59:19.083
♪ You and me been
finding each other ♪

59:19.167 --> 59:21.208
♪ For so long ♪

59:21.292 --> 59:23.708
- The Bee Gees' point of view
was about having hit records

59:23.791 --> 59:24.708
and being on the radio,

59:24.791 --> 59:27.208
and so the greatest gift
that you could give

59:27.292 --> 59:28.583
to your younger brother

59:28.666 --> 59:30.417
would be to give him
that success,

59:30.499 --> 59:33.333
to write songs with him,
to teach him to be a star.

59:33.417 --> 59:36.000
- ♪ I, I ♪

59:36.083 --> 59:39.916
♪ I just want to be
your everything ♪

59:40.000 --> 59:41.541
- And then suddenly,
out of nowhere,

59:41.624 --> 59:43.916
Andy had about three
number ones in a row.

59:44.000 --> 59:45.875
- He was a teen idol.

59:45.958 --> 59:47.958
There was talk about him
becoming a Bee Gee.

59:48.041 --> 59:50.208
I think Robert saw
he had a younger audience.

59:50.292 --> 59:52.208
Smart to keep him on his own.

59:52.292 --> 59:55.916
- ♪ Oh, if I ♪

59:56.000 --> 59:58.708
♪ If I stay here
without you, darling ♪

59:58.791 --> 1:00:00.708
♪ I will die ♪

1:00:00.791 --> 1:00:02.749
- All of a sudden,
he was the big thing.

1:00:02.833 --> 1:00:05.041
There was a period
when we lived in the shadow

1:00:05.125 --> 1:00:07.749
of Andy's band.

1:00:07.833 --> 1:00:11.541
- ♪ To be your everything ♪

1:00:11.624 --> 1:00:16.749
♪ ♪

1:00:16.833 --> 1:00:18.541
- After
"Children of the World" album,

1:00:18.624 --> 1:00:19.749
the next project,

1:00:19.833 --> 1:00:22.000
we were booked
to record in France

1:00:22.083 --> 1:00:24.916
'cause of the Elton John album
"Honky Château."

1:00:25.000 --> 1:00:26.125
It sounded great.

1:00:26.208 --> 1:00:29.250
- ♪ Bye-bye, château,
I must leave you ♪

1:00:29.333 --> 1:00:30.749
♪ Though it breaks my heart ♪

1:00:30.833 --> 1:00:33.000
- Robert sent us there--

1:00:33.083 --> 1:00:34.666
I think it was
some kind of tax thing.

1:00:34.749 --> 1:00:37.458
- We thought, "Well, if this
studio sounds that good,

1:00:37.541 --> 1:00:39.292
"hell yeah, let's go off
to France.

1:00:39.375 --> 1:00:40.333
Why not?

1:00:40.417 --> 1:00:43.333
[Elton John's "Honky Cat"]

1:00:43.417 --> 1:00:44.833
♪ ♪

1:00:44.916 --> 1:00:48.583
- It wasn't the honky château
that Elton John had used.

1:00:48.666 --> 1:00:51.666
[upbeat piano rock]

1:00:51.749 --> 1:00:53.624
- Now, château sounds
absolutely gorgeous,

1:00:53.708 --> 1:00:54.791
doesn't it?

1:00:54.875 --> 1:00:56.958
Beautiful building,
great grounds and gardens

1:00:57.041 --> 1:00:58.458
and ponds and fountains.

1:00:58.541 --> 1:00:59.458
No.

1:00:59.541 --> 1:01:01.458
[laughs]
It's nothing like that.

1:01:01.541 --> 1:01:05.333
It was a half-built castle,
no central heating, nothing,

1:01:05.417 --> 1:01:06.458
and it was a dump.

1:01:06.541 --> 1:01:08.958
- We seemed to be
in the middle of nowhere.

1:01:09.041 --> 1:01:11.083
Not a happy place to be.

1:01:11.167 --> 1:01:12.833
- It was really
kind of decrepit.

1:01:12.916 --> 1:01:15.292
I think it'd been used
to make porn movies.

1:01:15.375 --> 1:01:17.167
- This was not right.

1:01:17.250 --> 1:01:19.167
But because there was
a contract,

1:01:19.250 --> 1:01:22.417
we just decided to, you know,
plow on through.

1:01:22.499 --> 1:01:24.125
- We were going there
to mix a live album

1:01:24.208 --> 1:01:26.375
called "Here At Last...Live."

1:01:26.458 --> 1:01:28.333
- But also,
we were getting songs ready

1:01:28.417 --> 1:01:29.583
for our new studio album,

1:01:29.666 --> 1:01:32.000
which would be the follow-up
to "Children of the World."

1:01:32.083 --> 1:01:35.333
- And we got a call
from Robert Stigwood.

1:01:35.417 --> 1:01:38.333
[dramatic disco music]

1:01:38.417 --> 1:01:41.541
♪ ♪

1:01:41.624 --> 1:01:43.000
- A friend of mine, Nik Cohn,

1:01:43.083 --> 1:01:45.041
wrote this piece
for "New York" magazine,

1:01:45.125 --> 1:01:46.833
"Tribal Rites
of the New Saturday Night."

1:01:46.916 --> 1:01:50.375
Disco was really underway,
in Manhattan, anyway,

1:01:50.458 --> 1:01:52.041
but Nik Cohn's point was that

1:01:52.125 --> 1:01:54.000
rather than just being
underground gay clubs,

1:01:54.083 --> 1:01:56.375
straight couples are now going
to do the hustle

1:01:56.458 --> 1:01:58.541
on a Saturday night
in the suburbs.

1:01:58.624 --> 1:01:59.875
So I got Robert to buy
the film rights

1:01:59.958 --> 1:02:02.708
to a magazine article,
of which there was no story.

1:02:02.791 --> 1:02:04.417
But it caught
Robert's attention

1:02:04.499 --> 1:02:06.292
because he saw

1:02:06.375 --> 1:02:08.083
that that's a lead role
for an actor

1:02:08.167 --> 1:02:09.708
if it was a movie.

1:02:09.791 --> 1:02:10.749
He announced

1:02:10.833 --> 1:02:12.208
at the Beverly Hills Hotel
at breakfast,

1:02:12.292 --> 1:02:14.499
"I'm signing John Travolta
to a three-picture deal,"

1:02:14.583 --> 1:02:15.833
and people thought he was mad.

1:02:15.916 --> 1:02:17.499
He was a TV actor.

1:02:17.583 --> 1:02:19.833
No one gets a million dollars
for three pictures.

1:02:19.916 --> 1:02:21.708
Turned out to be the bargain
of the century, of course,

1:02:21.791 --> 1:02:23.417
because he got him
for "Grease"

1:02:23.499 --> 1:02:25.041
and the movie
we don't talk about,

1:02:25.125 --> 1:02:26.708
"Moment by Moment,"

1:02:26.791 --> 1:02:28.208
but two out of three's not bad.

1:02:28.292 --> 1:02:30.375
[David Shire's "Salsation"]

1:02:30.458 --> 1:02:31.875
I was still running
RSO Records,

1:02:31.958 --> 1:02:34.499
so my job was
to do the soundtrack,

1:02:34.583 --> 1:02:35.875
and my brief was,

1:02:35.958 --> 1:02:37.916
"Put all of your favorite
disco tracks

1:02:38.000 --> 1:02:39.125
"and everyone will play it
at a party

1:02:39.208 --> 1:02:40.417
and they'll
never stop dancing."

1:02:40.499 --> 1:02:43.458
[percussive dance music]

1:02:43.541 --> 1:02:45.583
♪ ♪

1:02:45.666 --> 1:02:47.417
These were comparatively easy,

1:02:47.499 --> 1:02:50.916
but we needed the Bee Gees
to write a few songs.

1:02:51.000 --> 1:02:52.541
- Phone call came through
from Robert,

1:02:52.624 --> 1:02:54.417
saying, "I wanna make
this film."

1:02:54.499 --> 1:02:56.749
- He said, "But I'm gonna need
two or three songs."

1:02:56.833 --> 1:02:59.083
- It wasn't the idea that they
would do the soundtrack.

1:02:59.167 --> 1:03:00.292
We knew they were busy.

1:03:00.375 --> 1:03:02.208
"But have you got some songs?"
Robert said,

1:03:02.292 --> 1:03:05.250
and they said, "Yeah, sure."

1:03:05.333 --> 1:03:07.749
- Robert said,
"I'm sending you a script."

1:03:07.833 --> 1:03:10.417
But we decided
not to read the script.

1:03:10.499 --> 1:03:12.624
- We weren't writing
the "Fever" music.

1:03:12.708 --> 1:03:16.417
We were writing our new album
and just having fun doing it.

1:03:16.499 --> 1:03:17.666
- They already had
a couple of tunes

1:03:17.749 --> 1:03:19.167
or some titles, anyway.

1:03:19.250 --> 1:03:20.624
We thought,
"Let's leave it with them."

1:03:20.708 --> 1:03:25.458
- What we ended up doing
was the demos of these songs.

1:03:25.541 --> 1:03:26.499
- And I was really surprised

1:03:26.583 --> 1:03:27.958
that, you know, it was
only a few weeks later

1:03:28.041 --> 1:03:30.083
we got the songs.

1:03:30.167 --> 1:03:34.749
We got a cassette,
and to this day, it's amazing.

1:03:34.833 --> 1:03:37.749
["Stayin' Alive"]

1:03:37.833 --> 1:03:39.875
♪ ♪

1:03:41.208 --> 1:03:42.458
[tape whirring]

1:03:42.541 --> 1:03:44.749
- ♪ On the waves of the air ♪

1:03:44.833 --> 1:03:46.125
[tape whirring]

1:03:46.208 --> 1:03:47.791
♪ You're in my life ♪

1:03:47.875 --> 1:03:48.958
- It was just one
after the other.

1:03:49.041 --> 1:03:51.333
You know, "Stayin' Alive,"
"More Than a Woman,"

1:03:51.417 --> 1:03:53.833
"How Deep Is Your Love,"
"If I Can't Have You,"

1:03:53.916 --> 1:03:54.958
"Night Fever"

1:03:55.041 --> 1:03:56.292
on one cassette.

1:03:56.375 --> 1:03:58.333
And I thought, "Yes.

1:03:58.417 --> 1:03:59.875
We've got a soundtrack."

1:03:59.958 --> 1:04:01.791
- You know,
you listen to that tape,

1:04:01.875 --> 1:04:03.499
whoever was playing
on those records,

1:04:03.583 --> 1:04:04.541
they would've been hits.

1:04:04.624 --> 1:04:05.791
Those songs are so good.

1:04:05.875 --> 1:04:07.958
You think, "Shit," you know?

1:04:08.041 --> 1:04:10.167
"That's so cool."

1:04:10.250 --> 1:04:11.458
- We had the demos,

1:04:11.541 --> 1:04:12.708
and then we went
into the process

1:04:12.791 --> 1:04:14.624
of making real records.

1:04:14.708 --> 1:04:17.624
- Barry and Carl and I lived
in that control room,

1:04:17.708 --> 1:04:19.167
I don't know, 16 hours a day.

1:04:19.250 --> 1:04:21.541
- Yeah.
That was the only thing to do.

1:04:21.624 --> 1:04:23.916
["Night Fever"]

1:04:24.000 --> 1:04:25.833
We recorded
"Night Fever" first.

1:04:25.916 --> 1:04:27.458
We actually had that
in the can.

1:04:27.541 --> 1:04:29.499
♪ ♪

1:04:29.583 --> 1:04:32.499
- Robert called and said,
"I need a title for the film."

1:04:32.583 --> 1:04:35.292
"What I've got at the moment,"
I said, "is two titles:

1:04:35.375 --> 1:04:37.499
'Stayin' Alive'
and 'Night Fever.'"

1:04:37.583 --> 1:04:40.499
And he said, "'Night Fever.'

1:04:40.583 --> 1:04:42.208
Hmm," he said, "sounds okay,"
he said,

1:04:42.292 --> 1:04:45.083
"but it sounds
a bit too pornographic.

1:04:45.167 --> 1:04:47.749
It'd need to be called
'Saturday Night,'" he said.

1:04:47.833 --> 1:04:49.916
So it turned
into "Saturday Night Fever."

1:04:50.000 --> 1:04:53.041
♪ Night fever, night fever ♪

1:04:53.125 --> 1:04:55.041
♪ We know how to do it ♪

1:04:55.125 --> 1:04:57.875
- We were editing "Fever"
on the lot at Paramount.

1:04:57.958 --> 1:05:00.333
I was deluged
by Paramount people saying,

1:05:00.417 --> 1:05:02.375
"How's your little disco movie
coming along?"

1:05:02.458 --> 1:05:03.916
So that was a bit patronizing.

1:05:04.000 --> 1:05:05.375
But the inspiring thing was

1:05:05.458 --> 1:05:07.333
that Stigwood,
during postproduction, said,

1:05:07.417 --> 1:05:08.749
"Why do we wait
for the release of the film?

1:05:08.833 --> 1:05:09.958
Let's put out a single now."

1:05:10.041 --> 1:05:12.250
And then he started
with the heads of Paramount,

1:05:12.333 --> 1:05:13.375
like, "How many theaters?"

1:05:13.458 --> 1:05:15.167
And they told him
something like 200.

1:05:15.250 --> 1:05:17.708
He said, "I'm releasing
the record in every city.

1:05:17.791 --> 1:05:19.875
Why can't it be
in every single city?"

1:05:19.958 --> 1:05:21.208
So they made a deal

1:05:21.292 --> 1:05:23.250
whereby if the record got
to the top 20,

1:05:23.333 --> 1:05:25.083
they would increase
the number of screens.

1:05:25.167 --> 1:05:27.208
If it got top ten,
they'd go more.

1:05:27.292 --> 1:05:28.749
He said,
"I need the first record

1:05:28.833 --> 1:05:29.791
to be number one."

1:05:29.875 --> 1:05:32.749
["How Deep Is Your Love"]

1:05:32.833 --> 1:05:34.375
[soft ballad]

1:05:34.458 --> 1:05:37.583
- Stigwood phoned up
and said to Barry,

1:05:37.666 --> 1:05:39.083
"I need the best love song

1:05:39.167 --> 1:05:42.083
you've ever written
for the movie."

1:05:42.167 --> 1:05:44.916
So we went into a room
in the château.

1:05:45.000 --> 1:05:46.916
Chopin had stayed there.

1:05:47.000 --> 1:05:48.541
So every time I looked
at this piano,

1:05:48.624 --> 1:05:51.208
I envisaged Chopin
sitting down and playing.

1:05:51.292 --> 1:05:52.749
♪ ♪

1:05:52.833 --> 1:05:53.875
I sat down at the piano

1:05:53.958 --> 1:05:56.417
and thought
of his Prelude in E Flat,

1:05:56.499 --> 1:05:59.875
and I knew Barry could sing
in E flat.

1:05:59.958 --> 1:06:01.250
When we were working
like that,

1:06:01.333 --> 1:06:03.083
I had a cassette player.

1:06:03.167 --> 1:06:06.083
- [vocalizing with piano]

1:06:06.167 --> 1:06:09.458
♪ ♪

1:06:09.541 --> 1:06:13.250
[indistinct chatter]

1:06:13.333 --> 1:06:17.292
♪ Love again ♪

1:06:17.375 --> 1:06:19.458
♪ Still in love ♪

1:06:19.541 --> 1:06:21.958
- And I'm sure it happened
at that point.

1:06:22.041 --> 1:06:24.208
Through
the stained glass window

1:06:24.292 --> 1:06:27.000
came a beam of sunlight,
you know?

1:06:27.083 --> 1:06:30.167
♪ Your eyes
in the morning sun ♪

1:06:30.250 --> 1:06:31.666
♪ ♪

1:06:31.749 --> 1:06:35.958
- ♪ I know your eyes
in the morning sun ♪

1:06:36.041 --> 1:06:40.666
♪ I feel you touch me
in the pouring rain ♪

1:06:40.749 --> 1:06:44.000
And that's a memory--
that'll last me all my life.

1:06:44.083 --> 1:06:46.208
Never forget it.

1:06:46.292 --> 1:06:47.333
Never forget it.

1:06:47.417 --> 1:06:50.624
♪ ♪

1:06:50.708 --> 1:06:51.666
- You know, all the feelings,

1:06:51.749 --> 1:06:53.208
all the emotions
are still there.

1:06:53.292 --> 1:06:55.875
When you talk about it,
it all comes back, you know?

1:06:55.958 --> 1:06:58.083
♪ ♪

1:06:58.167 --> 1:07:01.375
I have a--

1:07:01.458 --> 1:07:04.666
my heart is in that song.

1:07:04.749 --> 1:07:08.958
- ♪ I know your eyes
in the morning sun ♪

1:07:09.041 --> 1:07:13.749
♪ I feel you touch me
in the pouring rain ♪

1:07:13.833 --> 1:07:18.333
♪ And the moment
that you wander far from me ♪

1:07:18.417 --> 1:07:22.833
♪ I wanna feel you
in my arms again ♪

1:07:22.916 --> 1:07:27.541
♪ And you come to me
on a summer breeze ♪

1:07:27.624 --> 1:07:32.333
♪ Keep me warm in your love,
then you softly leave ♪

1:07:32.417 --> 1:07:35.875
♪ And it's me
you need to show ♪

1:07:35.958 --> 1:07:38.916
♪ How deep is your love? ♪
- ♪ How deep is your love? ♪

1:07:39.000 --> 1:07:42.083
all: ♪ How deep is your love? ♪

1:07:42.167 --> 1:07:45.167
♪ I really mean to learn ♪

1:07:45.250 --> 1:07:49.666
♪ 'Cause we're living
in a world of fools ♪

1:07:49.749 --> 1:07:52.541
♪ Breaking us down ♪

1:07:52.624 --> 1:07:57.041
♪ When they all should
let us be ♪

1:07:57.125 --> 1:08:01.417
♪ We belong to you and me ♪

1:08:01.499 --> 1:08:03.041
♪ ♪

1:08:03.125 --> 1:08:05.541
- Everything came together.

1:08:05.624 --> 1:08:08.417
But sadly,
Dennis had had some bad news.

1:08:08.499 --> 1:08:11.624
- My mother was in hospital.
She had Alzheimer's.

1:08:11.708 --> 1:08:14.875
So, you know, I told Barry
what was going on.

1:08:14.958 --> 1:08:18.292
He said, you know, "Get Dick
to book you a flight now."

1:08:18.375 --> 1:08:22.375
- He had to fly back to the UK,
and we had no drummer.

1:08:22.458 --> 1:08:24.417
- We thought, "Well, we gotta
carry on writing

1:08:24.499 --> 1:08:26.916
and getting
these tracks together."

1:08:27.000 --> 1:08:29.250
[distorted rewinding drum]

1:08:29.333 --> 1:08:30.875
- Okay, I know now.

1:08:32.333 --> 1:08:35.000
[drumbeat playing]

1:08:35.083 --> 1:08:37.375
- When I was at Berklee,
I had studied things

1:08:37.458 --> 1:08:39.041
where they were
moving tapes around

1:08:39.125 --> 1:08:41.541
and make sort of these
interesting sonic loops.

1:08:41.624 --> 1:08:43.749
And when Dennis was not there,

1:08:43.833 --> 1:08:46.125
I said,
"Well, why don't we just

1:08:46.208 --> 1:08:47.458
"take a bar
out of 'Night Fever'?

1:08:47.541 --> 1:08:48.833
"I think
it's a little slower tempo.

1:08:48.916 --> 1:08:50.333
"We'll slow it down
a little bit

1:08:50.417 --> 1:08:51.791
and see if we can make a loop
out of it."

1:08:51.875 --> 1:08:54.833
["Night Fever" playing]

1:08:54.916 --> 1:08:57.666
♪ ♪

1:08:57.749 --> 1:09:00.833
We found a bar that we thought
had a really nice feel to it.

1:09:00.916 --> 1:09:02.458
We copied it over to a...

1:09:02.541 --> 1:09:05.333
- 1/2 inch four-track.
- 1/2 inch four-track.

1:09:05.417 --> 1:09:08.749
- And spliced the tape
into a loop.

1:09:08.833 --> 1:09:09.791
Tape dump.

1:09:09.875 --> 1:09:13.458
[drumbeat playing]

1:09:13.541 --> 1:09:15.000
- I was pretty good
at imagining

1:09:15.083 --> 1:09:16.624
what you might be able to do,

1:09:16.708 --> 1:09:18.749
but Carl was able
to make it happen.

1:09:18.833 --> 1:09:22.624
- It was just necessity
being the mother of invention.

1:09:22.708 --> 1:09:24.958
- No one had taken
a drumbeat before

1:09:25.041 --> 1:09:27.541
and created a two-bar phrase.

1:09:27.624 --> 1:09:29.791
We were breaking new ground.

1:09:29.875 --> 1:09:30.958
- Perfect. Good.

1:09:31.041 --> 1:09:34.541
- This is the first time
we had ever taken the song

1:09:34.624 --> 1:09:36.875
and built it piece by piece
from the ground up,

1:09:36.958 --> 1:09:38.458
and we started
with this drum loop.

1:09:38.541 --> 1:09:40.000
[drumbeat]

1:09:40.083 --> 1:09:41.791
And then we did a bass line.

1:09:41.875 --> 1:09:43.666
[funky bass line]

1:09:43.749 --> 1:09:44.833
And then a guitar part.

1:09:44.916 --> 1:09:47.791
[swinging guitar riff]

1:09:47.875 --> 1:09:49.833
♪ ♪

1:09:49.916 --> 1:09:53.250
Never again would we rely
as much on the liveness.

1:09:53.333 --> 1:09:54.208
We would always know

1:09:54.292 --> 1:09:55.541
that we could
construct the song

1:09:55.624 --> 1:09:56.833
and put the pieces together

1:09:56.916 --> 1:09:59.499
based on the original vision
of the song

1:09:59.583 --> 1:10:01.000
and how we imagined it.

1:10:01.083 --> 1:10:04.000
["Stayin' Alive"]

1:10:04.083 --> 1:10:07.624
- I got back to the sessions,
and there was just a buzz.

1:10:07.708 --> 1:10:08.624
- When we did it, we thought,

1:10:08.708 --> 1:10:10.167
"We're just doing this
temporarily,"

1:10:10.250 --> 1:10:11.499
and when Dennis comes back,

1:10:11.583 --> 1:10:13.167
we'll replace it
with real drums,"

1:10:13.250 --> 1:10:15.875
but what happened is,
the feel was so amazing

1:10:15.958 --> 1:10:17.041
that we couldn't get rid of it.

1:10:17.125 --> 1:10:19.375
- He played it for me,
and I could tell

1:10:19.458 --> 1:10:21.000
from the first listen.

1:10:21.083 --> 1:10:24.541
I said, "Man, that is amazing."

1:10:24.624 --> 1:10:26.417
- When you listen
to the drum track

1:10:26.499 --> 1:10:29.000
on "Stayin' Alive,"
like, by itself,

1:10:29.083 --> 1:10:31.708
it's really this super rugged,
like, tough thing.

1:10:31.791 --> 1:10:35.875
It's like...
[mimicking drumbeat]

1:10:35.958 --> 1:10:37.499
It's not pretty or pop
like you remember.

1:10:37.583 --> 1:10:38.499
It's pretty tough.

1:10:38.583 --> 1:10:41.708
♪ ♪

1:10:41.791 --> 1:10:43.499
- "Stayin' Alive"
was the influence

1:10:43.583 --> 1:10:45.541
that New York gave to us.

1:10:45.624 --> 1:10:47.041
And the energy level
at that point

1:10:47.125 --> 1:10:50.333
in the late '70s
was really that, you know?

1:10:50.417 --> 1:10:51.875
It's survival. It's survival.

1:10:51.958 --> 1:10:52.875
- This is '77.

1:10:52.958 --> 1:10:54.749
Everybody know
that time is hard now.

1:10:54.833 --> 1:10:56.250
You know,
if I was out there myself,

1:10:56.333 --> 1:10:57.791
I would've got
what I wanted too.

1:10:57.875 --> 1:10:58.916
- You were not
among the looters?

1:10:59.000 --> 1:11:00.749
- No, I wasn't.
Unfortunate.

1:11:00.833 --> 1:11:01.958
- Do you feel
personally threatened

1:11:02.041 --> 1:11:03.250
by the .44 Caliber Killer?

1:11:03.333 --> 1:11:04.417
- Yes, I do.

1:11:04.499 --> 1:11:05.583
I don't feel free to go out,

1:11:05.666 --> 1:11:08.083
to walk the streets
or go out at all.

1:11:08.167 --> 1:11:10.208
- Very few people realize

1:11:10.292 --> 1:11:11.583
it's to do with anything
but dance,

1:11:11.666 --> 1:11:14.125
but the lyrics don't talk
about dance at all,

1:11:14.208 --> 1:11:16.583
and the lyrics
very obviously state

1:11:16.666 --> 1:11:18.125
the scenario of survival.

1:11:18.208 --> 1:11:20.250
- ♪ Whether you're a brother
or whether you're a mother ♪

1:11:20.333 --> 1:11:22.916
♪ You're stayin' alive,
stayin' alive ♪

1:11:23.000 --> 1:11:24.958
♪ Feel the city breaking
and everybody shaking ♪

1:11:25.041 --> 1:11:27.708
♪ And we're stayin' alive,
stayin' alive ♪

1:11:27.791 --> 1:11:29.916
♪ Ah, ha, ha, ha ♪

1:11:30.000 --> 1:11:31.499
♪ Stayin' alive,
stayin' alive ♪

1:11:31.583 --> 1:11:34.417
- If you think about...
♪ Ha, ha, ha, ha ♪

1:11:34.499 --> 1:11:37.624
I mean, that could very easily
have just been a horn line,

1:11:37.708 --> 1:11:39.624
but instead,
their voices are so sick,

1:11:39.708 --> 1:11:42.250
they're like,
"Nah, we're gonna sing it."

1:11:42.333 --> 1:11:43.250
♪ ♪

1:11:43.333 --> 1:11:46.375
- ♪ Oh, when you walk ♪

1:11:46.458 --> 1:11:49.041
- The general fever
at the time

1:11:49.125 --> 1:11:51.624
was, "You must see this film."

1:11:51.708 --> 1:11:55.292
The songs precipitated
the interest.

1:11:55.375 --> 1:11:57.958
It was
this cultural phenomenon.

1:11:58.041 --> 1:12:00.791
["More Than a Woman"]

1:12:00.875 --> 1:12:02.125
- In the first week
of release,

1:12:02.208 --> 1:12:05.167
they were having to hire
extra staff in some cinemas

1:12:05.250 --> 1:12:06.624
to stop them dancing
in the aisles.

1:12:06.708 --> 1:12:08.958
- ♪ Girl, I've know you
very well ♪

1:12:09.041 --> 1:12:10.333
♪ I've seen you growing
every day ♪

1:12:10.417 --> 1:12:11.749
- Other movies
were being put back

1:12:11.833 --> 1:12:14.208
or taken out of other screens
to make room for "Fever."

1:12:14.292 --> 1:12:16.666
I mean, it was really
quite a phenomenon.

1:12:16.749 --> 1:12:19.333
John took me aside
at one point and said,

1:12:19.417 --> 1:12:20.458
"Hey, what do you think?

1:12:20.541 --> 1:12:23.292
You think maybe
an Academy Award nomination?"

1:12:23.375 --> 1:12:24.791
And I'm thinking,
"Jesus Christ, no."

1:12:24.875 --> 1:12:26.292
I mean, this is ridiculous.

1:12:26.375 --> 1:12:28.333
It's a dance movie, you know?

1:12:28.417 --> 1:12:29.458
He had the last laugh.

1:12:29.541 --> 1:12:31.833
- And John Travolta
in "Saturday Night Fever."

1:12:31.916 --> 1:12:34.624
[cheers and applause]

1:12:34.708 --> 1:12:35.666
- The "Fever" thing happened.

1:12:35.749 --> 1:12:37.167
That's when
everything exploded.

1:12:37.250 --> 1:12:39.000
Other record companies
were printing it.

1:12:39.083 --> 1:12:40.958
Then our record company
couldn't keep up the pace.

1:12:41.041 --> 1:12:42.000
- We didn't know
what was going on

1:12:42.083 --> 1:12:44.958
because this was
just a soundtrack.

1:12:45.041 --> 1:12:46.041
- Could I ask, for example,

1:12:46.125 --> 1:12:48.541
what "Saturday Night Fever"
has grossed thus far?

1:12:48.624 --> 1:12:50.833
- Around 110 million.
[audience cheers]

1:12:50.916 --> 1:12:53.666
At the moment.
In America.

1:12:53.749 --> 1:12:55.499
- In America?
- In America, yeah.

1:12:55.583 --> 1:12:56.833
- And the album?

1:12:56.916 --> 1:12:58.958
- The album, I think,
is nearing

1:12:59.041 --> 1:13:02.292
18 million
double albums worldwide.

1:13:02.375 --> 1:13:04.208
- But I mean, that would be
the record-breaker of all time.

1:13:04.292 --> 1:13:07.375
- Yes, it's already
the biggest-grossing album

1:13:07.458 --> 1:13:09.041
in the history of music.

1:13:09.125 --> 1:13:11.541
- The statistics
are just incredible.

1:13:11.624 --> 1:13:14.250
Four singles
from "Saturday Night Fever"

1:13:14.333 --> 1:13:17.208
have hit number one
since the album was released,

1:13:17.292 --> 1:13:20.333
more than from any other
new album in history.

1:13:20.417 --> 1:13:22.208
That's just a few
of the statistics

1:13:22.292 --> 1:13:25.041
that lead to gold records
like this.

1:13:25.125 --> 1:13:27.125
And so it's my privilege
to say,

1:13:27.208 --> 1:13:29.417
ladies and gentlemen,
will you welcome

1:13:29.499 --> 1:13:31.041
the Bee Gees!

1:13:31.125 --> 1:13:32.208
[cheers and applause]

1:13:32.292 --> 1:13:33.749
[Walter Murphy's
"A Fifth of Beethoven"]

1:13:33.833 --> 1:13:37.250
Has it changed your lives,
the enormous success of it?

1:13:37.333 --> 1:13:38.833
[disco-tinged classical music]

1:13:38.916 --> 1:13:41.791
- Yes, I can safely say
it's changed our lives.

1:13:41.875 --> 1:13:44.250
[camera shutters clicking]

1:13:44.333 --> 1:13:46.791
- The Bee Gees, I think,
were stunned by their success.

1:13:46.875 --> 1:13:49.250
♪ ♪

1:13:49.333 --> 1:13:51.875
- We were aware we were
creating a specific sound,

1:13:51.958 --> 1:13:53.375
but we didn't know
what it was gonna do.

1:13:53.458 --> 1:13:55.125
♪ ♪

1:13:55.208 --> 1:13:57.250
- It did end up with them
having half the top ten

1:13:57.333 --> 1:13:59.125
with these songs.

1:13:59.208 --> 1:14:00.333
It was extraordinary.

1:14:00.417 --> 1:14:01.749
Kind of the same domination
the Beatles had

1:14:01.833 --> 1:14:03.292
in the '60s in America.

1:14:03.375 --> 1:14:05.791
♪ ♪

1:14:05.875 --> 1:14:08.292
- They were just everywhere.

1:14:08.375 --> 1:14:10.250
- But our own friends
don't treat us the same way.

1:14:10.333 --> 1:14:11.749
- What, from a distance,
they treat you?

1:14:11.833 --> 1:14:14.083
- Well, I was speaking to one
of my friends the other day,

1:14:14.167 --> 1:14:15.916
and as he was cleaning
my shoes, I said, "Listen."

1:14:16.000 --> 1:14:17.292
[laughter]

1:14:17.375 --> 1:14:18.916
- Stigwood said,

1:14:19.000 --> 1:14:20.583
"Let's give the band
half a point or a quarter."

1:14:20.666 --> 1:14:23.791
Now, that's not a percentage.
That's a tiny amount of money.

1:14:23.875 --> 1:14:25.125
- But when you sell
as many copies

1:14:25.208 --> 1:14:27.708
as "Saturday Night Fever" sold,

1:14:27.791 --> 1:14:29.833
it turns out to be big money.

1:14:29.916 --> 1:14:31.833
♪ ♪

1:14:31.916 --> 1:14:32.916
- What are you doing

1:14:33.000 --> 1:14:34.541
with these millions
of dollars?

1:14:34.624 --> 1:14:36.292
- What are you doing
with your millions of dollars?

1:14:36.375 --> 1:14:38.666
- Oh, no.
[laughter]

1:14:38.749 --> 1:14:40.458
- It is the biggest night
of the year

1:14:40.541 --> 1:14:41.833
for people
in the recording industry,

1:14:41.916 --> 1:14:42.916
the Grammy Awards.

1:14:43.000 --> 1:14:45.458
- And the winner is
"Saturday Night Fever."

1:14:45.541 --> 1:14:48.250
[cheers and applause]
Whoo!

1:14:48.333 --> 1:14:51.292
- For a soundtrack to win
Best Album was amazing.

1:14:51.375 --> 1:14:52.791
It went on to be
one of the best-selling albums

1:14:52.875 --> 1:14:54.167
in history.

1:14:54.250 --> 1:14:56.791
♪ ♪

1:14:56.875 --> 1:14:59.125
- We didn't know we were
defining the culture.

1:14:59.208 --> 1:15:01.250
We were just still
Barry, Maurice, and Robin

1:15:01.333 --> 1:15:02.749
wondering what the hell's
going on.

1:15:02.833 --> 1:15:09.708
♪ ♪

1:15:11.083 --> 1:15:13.208
- The fever
has been contagious.

1:15:13.292 --> 1:15:16.000
Discos, the places in which
to dance away the night

1:15:16.083 --> 1:15:18.167
and the morning hours,
are thriving.

1:15:18.250 --> 1:15:19.791
What the fever has done
is made

1:15:19.875 --> 1:15:22.916
just about anything
related to disco profitable.

1:15:23.000 --> 1:15:24.499
Where there's money
to be made,

1:15:24.583 --> 1:15:26.292
disco is the business.

1:15:26.375 --> 1:15:29.499
- We didn't categorize
our songs as disco,

1:15:29.583 --> 1:15:31.916
but then we weren't thinking
that way at all.

1:15:32.000 --> 1:15:33.333
We were just thinking
about writing songs

1:15:33.417 --> 1:15:35.624
based on this discovery
of this falsetto voice

1:15:35.708 --> 1:15:37.833
and how well
that seemed to work.

1:15:37.916 --> 1:15:39.041
- What the Bee Gees brought,

1:15:39.125 --> 1:15:41.833
I always felt
they brought melody to disco.

1:15:41.916 --> 1:15:45.167
Most disco at that point
was melody-free, you know?

1:15:45.250 --> 1:15:47.583
This was a different take
on disco.

1:15:47.666 --> 1:15:49.458
It was completely for--

1:15:49.541 --> 1:15:51.541
for the broadest
possible audience.

1:15:51.624 --> 1:15:52.749
- You got the lyrics?
- Yes.

1:15:52.833 --> 1:15:53.791
- Great.
- Right here.

1:15:53.875 --> 1:15:55.250
- Okay. Let's go.
- Straight into it.

1:15:55.333 --> 1:15:56.749
[guitar strumming]

1:15:56.833 --> 1:15:58.708
One, two, three, four.

1:15:58.791 --> 1:16:02.208
[rough disco music playing]

1:16:02.292 --> 1:16:03.833
Right.
Okay.

1:16:03.916 --> 1:16:07.041
♪ ♪

1:16:07.125 --> 1:16:10.208
[both vocalizing]

1:16:10.292 --> 1:16:12.875
♪ ♪

1:16:12.958 --> 1:16:15.375
- Hey, guys.
- It's too slow.

1:16:15.458 --> 1:16:16.583
It would be nice
if we could find a bigger sound

1:16:16.666 --> 1:16:17.666
for that solo.

1:16:17.749 --> 1:16:18.666
- Great.

1:16:18.749 --> 1:16:19.666
- The way we rehearsed it
last night.

1:16:19.749 --> 1:16:21.916
- All right.
[punchy synth notes]

1:16:22.000 --> 1:16:23.041
- Yeah.
Just like that.

1:16:23.125 --> 1:16:24.041
Yeah. Beautiful.

1:16:24.125 --> 1:16:25.375
Bring that sound in.
That's great.

1:16:25.458 --> 1:16:26.791
[synth note]
Yeah.

1:16:26.875 --> 1:16:28.375
- Okay, let's try it again.
- Okay.

1:16:28.458 --> 1:16:30.583
One, two, three, four.

1:16:30.666 --> 1:16:32.125
♪ Tragedy ♪

1:16:32.208 --> 1:16:34.125
♪ When the feeling's gone
and you can't go on ♪

1:16:34.208 --> 1:16:36.250
♪ It's tragedy ♪

1:16:36.333 --> 1:16:38.458
♪ When the morning cries
and you don't know why ♪

1:16:38.541 --> 1:16:40.250
♪ It's hard to bear ♪

1:16:40.333 --> 1:16:42.250
♪ With no one beside you ♪

1:16:42.333 --> 1:16:44.749
♪ You're going nowhere ♪

1:16:44.833 --> 1:16:45.916
♪ ♪

1:16:46.000 --> 1:16:47.208
♪ Ah ♪

1:16:47.292 --> 1:16:49.041
- When we brought out
"Spirits Having Flown,"

1:16:49.125 --> 1:16:51.083
it did phenomenally well.

1:16:51.167 --> 1:16:54.250
At the same time, "Fever" was
still in the top ten.

1:16:54.333 --> 1:16:56.749
You know, we could've left it
another year,

1:16:56.833 --> 1:16:59.333
and it still probably would've
been a little too soon

1:16:59.417 --> 1:17:01.458
with what was going on
with "Fever."

1:17:01.541 --> 1:17:04.541
[Odyssey's
"Native New Yorker"]

1:17:04.624 --> 1:17:07.958
[jazzy disco music]

1:17:08.041 --> 1:17:10.583
♪ ♪

1:17:10.666 --> 1:17:11.833
- Good morning, everybody.

1:17:11.916 --> 1:17:13.791
Charley Steiner, 99X.

1:17:13.875 --> 1:17:15.624
As is per usual for Monday,

1:17:15.708 --> 1:17:19.125
a very busy day
coming into town.

1:17:19.208 --> 1:17:21.833
I'm working
at a top 40 station

1:17:21.916 --> 1:17:23.791
in New York, big one,

1:17:23.875 --> 1:17:26.583
WXLO, but it was known as 99X.

1:17:26.666 --> 1:17:29.541
And I was
the morning news guy.

1:17:29.624 --> 1:17:33.499
Most radio stations
had a very small playlist,

1:17:33.583 --> 1:17:37.791
and the Bee Gees probably had
the top four, top five hits

1:17:37.875 --> 1:17:38.875
any given week.

1:17:38.958 --> 1:17:40.958
- 13 CFRW.

1:17:41.041 --> 1:17:42.250
Music of the Bee Gees
and "Tragedy."

1:17:42.333 --> 1:17:43.292
- Get out on the dance floor

1:17:43.375 --> 1:17:45.125
and do one more
with the Bee Gees.

1:17:45.208 --> 1:17:46.791
- All the Gibb brothers
together, the Bee Gees,

1:17:46.875 --> 1:17:47.958
"You Should Be Dancing."

1:17:48.041 --> 1:17:49.499
You should be shaking
that thing one time.

1:17:49.583 --> 1:17:52.333
- And for those of us
at the radio station,

1:17:52.417 --> 1:17:53.499
we're--
[laughs]

1:17:53.583 --> 1:17:55.125
We're gonna take hostages.

1:17:55.208 --> 1:17:56.875
["Too Much Heaven"]

1:17:56.958 --> 1:17:59.167
- And if you haven't had
enough Bee Gees music yet,

1:17:59.250 --> 1:18:01.333
well, we've got more.

1:18:01.417 --> 1:18:04.167
Guess you could kind of
call it over-giving.

1:18:04.250 --> 1:18:05.666
- And then Andy Gibb too.

1:18:05.749 --> 1:18:09.125
He was like the caboose
on this musical train.

1:18:09.208 --> 1:18:12.958
It was like waves in the sea.

1:18:13.041 --> 1:18:17.208
- ♪ Nobody gets
too much heaven no more ♪

1:18:17.292 --> 1:18:19.375
- You're right on the top
of the world.

1:18:19.458 --> 1:18:22.666
What is it that drives you
back on the road?

1:18:22.749 --> 1:18:25.375
- When we make records
and when we're in the studio,

1:18:25.458 --> 1:18:28.333
we never really see
who buys those records.

1:18:28.417 --> 1:18:30.292
I think getting on the road
means that to us.

1:18:30.375 --> 1:18:33.208
It means that we come
face-to-face with people

1:18:33.292 --> 1:18:34.833
to whom our records mean a lot.

1:18:34.916 --> 1:18:38.208
But to be sure, doing a tour
is an enormous amount of work.

1:18:38.292 --> 1:18:40.541
The only thing that I noticed
that's not right is,

1:18:40.624 --> 1:18:41.875
it doesn't actually say
the Bee Gees,

1:18:41.958 --> 1:18:43.041
and I think
it should actually--

1:18:43.125 --> 1:18:44.125
the Bee Gees' name should be--

1:18:44.208 --> 1:18:46.583
it should be "Bee Gees,
Spirits Having Flown."

1:18:46.666 --> 1:18:49.208
["Love You Inside Out"]

1:18:49.292 --> 1:18:52.000
- The '79 tour
was a complete sellout.

1:18:52.083 --> 1:18:55.000
- The Bee Gees hadn't toured
since 1976,

1:18:55.083 --> 1:18:56.624
and that tour was a promotion

1:18:56.708 --> 1:18:58.083
for the "Spirits Having Flown"
album,

1:18:58.167 --> 1:18:59.417
but it was celebrating

1:18:59.499 --> 1:19:01.541
"Saturday Night Fever"
as well, you know.

1:19:01.624 --> 1:19:03.541
- 25,000 people
are supposed to be here.

1:19:03.624 --> 1:19:04.791
- It's gonna be great.

1:19:04.875 --> 1:19:06.375
- You don't mind the Bee Gees
in the rain?

1:19:06.458 --> 1:19:07.916
- No.
- No, not at all.

1:19:08.000 --> 1:19:09.916
- We've been here
since 9:00 this morning.

1:19:10.000 --> 1:19:12.041
- They're worth waiting
in the rain for.

1:19:12.125 --> 1:19:14.583
- I mean, it was huge.

1:19:14.666 --> 1:19:16.749
Dodger Stadium,
places like that.

1:19:16.833 --> 1:19:18.875
We used to dream of this.

1:19:18.958 --> 1:19:20.958
Having people in the audience
like Barbra Streisand

1:19:21.041 --> 1:19:22.749
watching your show
and loving it, you know,

1:19:22.833 --> 1:19:25.292
I mean, these are fantasies.

1:19:25.375 --> 1:19:27.083
You're in a sort
of goldfish bowl on tour.

1:19:27.167 --> 1:19:28.417
You know, it's like,
you don't see much

1:19:28.499 --> 1:19:29.417
of what's going on out there.

1:19:29.499 --> 1:19:31.083
- Anyway, the most
important thing is

1:19:31.167 --> 1:19:32.292
what we're gonna do
after the show.

1:19:32.375 --> 1:19:33.708
[laughter]
- What do you wanna do?

1:19:33.791 --> 1:19:35.083
- That's what we're here
to talk about.

1:19:35.167 --> 1:19:36.583
- It's here.

1:19:36.666 --> 1:19:38.417
The Disco Body Shaper,

1:19:38.499 --> 1:19:40.666
the brand-new
exerciser sensation

1:19:40.749 --> 1:19:42.250
that's sweeping the country.

1:19:42.333 --> 1:19:44.083
Send for yours today.

1:19:44.167 --> 1:19:47.499
- Buy it today,
be a disco star tonight.

1:19:47.583 --> 1:19:49.583
- Let's disco to Burger King.

1:19:49.666 --> 1:19:51.749
- It all goes back
to one thing

1:19:51.833 --> 1:19:53.417
and the same thing
that's happening now:

1:19:53.499 --> 1:19:54.583
greed.

1:19:54.666 --> 1:19:56.292
[Rick Dees' "Disco Duck"]

1:19:56.375 --> 1:20:00.292
Greed is the thing
that happens in people

1:20:00.375 --> 1:20:03.333
that really ruins
a lot of shit.

1:20:03.417 --> 1:20:04.958
- ♪ Went to a party
the other night ♪

1:20:05.041 --> 1:20:06.000
- In the beginning,

1:20:06.083 --> 1:20:07.958
you would buy
a disco-bannered record

1:20:08.041 --> 1:20:09.791
and it would be a great song,

1:20:09.875 --> 1:20:11.666
no matter which one
you picked out.

1:20:11.749 --> 1:20:14.499
- ♪ Moving my feet
to the disco beat ♪

1:20:14.583 --> 1:20:18.833
- But then some executive
in diapers decided,

1:20:18.916 --> 1:20:21.000
"Let's put 'disco'

1:20:21.083 --> 1:20:23.749
on all these records
we wanna sell,"

1:20:23.833 --> 1:20:26.125
and it wasn't
good music anymore.

1:20:26.208 --> 1:20:27.958
It was garbage.

1:20:28.041 --> 1:20:29.624
- ♪ Look at me ♪

1:20:29.708 --> 1:20:33.125
♪ I'm the disco duck ♪

1:20:33.208 --> 1:20:35.749
- [Donald Duck voice]
Ah, get down, mama.

1:20:35.833 --> 1:20:37.000
- So that was, I think,
the straw

1:20:37.083 --> 1:20:38.208
that broke the camel's back.

1:20:38.292 --> 1:20:39.499
- ♪ Disco ♪

1:20:39.583 --> 1:20:40.708
♪ Disco duck ♪

1:20:40.791 --> 1:20:42.916
- Disco
as a purely musical form

1:20:43.000 --> 1:20:45.000
is, you know, dead.

1:20:45.083 --> 1:20:46.000
- I hated it.

1:20:46.083 --> 1:20:47.458
Couldn't think
of anything redeem--

1:20:47.541 --> 1:20:48.666
it was old people's music.

1:20:48.749 --> 1:20:51.333
- It was a very easy thing

1:20:51.417 --> 1:20:54.833
to get involved with
for commercial reasons.

1:20:54.916 --> 1:20:56.499
- [Donald Duck voice]
♪ Everybody's doing ♪

1:20:56.583 --> 1:20:58.375
♪ The disco ♪

1:20:58.458 --> 1:20:59.833
- I'd like to show you

1:20:59.916 --> 1:21:02.208
how we destroy
the disco records.

1:21:02.292 --> 1:21:04.499
This is how I do it.

1:21:04.583 --> 1:21:06.833
Have to kind of get worked up
a little bit.

1:21:06.916 --> 1:21:08.125
It's like--
- Yeah.

1:21:08.208 --> 1:21:10.000
- And then I just--

1:21:10.083 --> 1:21:11.958
[music slows to a stop]

1:21:12.041 --> 1:21:13.333
Oof.
That felt good.

1:21:13.417 --> 1:21:14.458
[Ted Nugent's "Stranglehold"]

1:21:14.541 --> 1:21:16.333
- Our next guest tonight
is Steve Dahl.

1:21:16.417 --> 1:21:19.208
And he is a disc jockey
for station WLUP-FM

1:21:19.292 --> 1:21:20.875
out in Chicago, Illinois,

1:21:20.958 --> 1:21:22.541
and he hates disco music.

1:21:22.624 --> 1:21:25.375
- Steve Dahl was kind of hard
to avoid in Chicago.

1:21:25.458 --> 1:21:28.541
[bold rock music]

1:21:28.624 --> 1:21:34.041
♪ ♪

1:21:34.125 --> 1:21:36.541
Steve Dahl was on the radio
saying, "Disco sucks.

1:21:36.624 --> 1:21:38.541
Disco sucks."

1:21:38.624 --> 1:21:40.541
I was 14.

1:21:40.624 --> 1:21:42.541
I listened to the Loop,

1:21:42.624 --> 1:21:45.666
the radio station that this
kind of centered around.

1:21:45.749 --> 1:21:47.708
- He brings helium
to the studio,

1:21:47.791 --> 1:21:50.417
inhales it and imitates
the Bee Gees on the air,

1:21:50.499 --> 1:21:52.208
and then breaks up
their records.

1:21:52.292 --> 1:21:54.167
- [high-pitched]
♪ How deep is your love? ♪

1:21:54.250 --> 1:21:57.083
[laughter]
♪ How deep is your love? ♪

1:21:57.167 --> 1:22:01.250
♪ I really need to know ♪

1:22:01.333 --> 1:22:04.916
- You know, when you do
all those things,

1:22:05.000 --> 1:22:06.458
like put out garbage,

1:22:06.541 --> 1:22:10.250
you know, have radio
being--feeling ostracized

1:22:10.333 --> 1:22:13.250
and a lot of straight people
feeling threatened,

1:22:13.333 --> 1:22:17.250
it creates a real poison.

1:22:17.333 --> 1:22:19.624
[crowd cheering]

1:22:19.708 --> 1:22:21.041
- Hello again, everybody.

1:22:21.125 --> 1:22:23.916
Harry Caray and Jimmy Piersall
from Comiskey Park,

1:22:24.000 --> 1:22:27.417
where we're gonna have
a wild night tonight,

1:22:27.499 --> 1:22:29.041
a twilight doubleheader.

1:22:29.125 --> 1:22:31.583
- I was an usher
at Comiskey Park.

1:22:31.666 --> 1:22:33.125
That was my first job.

1:22:33.208 --> 1:22:36.250
- Look at that crowd
out there.

1:22:36.333 --> 1:22:37.375
- 50,000 people,

1:22:37.458 --> 1:22:38.708
the largest crowd
of the season,

1:22:38.791 --> 1:22:41.250
showed up
at Chicago's Comiskey Park.

1:22:41.333 --> 1:22:43.125
Many had come
for Disco Demolition Night,

1:22:43.250 --> 1:22:44.916
a promotional gimmick.

1:22:45.000 --> 1:22:47.958
15,000 others had to be
turned away.

1:22:48.041 --> 1:22:49.125
- Steve Dahl says,

1:22:49.208 --> 1:22:52.333
"We're gonna let everybody in
the White Sox park

1:22:52.417 --> 1:22:55.417
"for 98¢

1:22:55.499 --> 1:22:57.250
"if you bring a disco record,

1:22:57.333 --> 1:22:58.791
"and we're gonna blow
those records up

1:22:58.875 --> 1:23:00.333
in the middle of center field."

1:23:00.417 --> 1:23:02.624
[tense music]

1:23:02.708 --> 1:23:05.125
We're letting people in.

1:23:05.208 --> 1:23:09.250
I pointed out
to my chief usher,

1:23:09.333 --> 1:23:11.833
"That record, that record,
that record,

1:23:11.916 --> 1:23:14.167
"that record, that record,
that record,

1:23:14.250 --> 1:23:16.250
"those aren't disco records.

1:23:16.333 --> 1:23:18.583
Those are just--
those are R&B records."

1:23:18.666 --> 1:23:20.875
♪ ♪

1:23:20.958 --> 1:23:24.000
And the thing that I noticed

1:23:24.083 --> 1:23:26.333
more than anything

1:23:26.417 --> 1:23:29.167
was just mostly Black records.

1:23:29.250 --> 1:23:30.791
[crowd cheering]

1:23:30.875 --> 1:23:31.958
- At the same time

1:23:32.041 --> 1:23:34.000
all this stuff is going down
in Chicago,

1:23:34.083 --> 1:23:35.833
we were playing the stadiums.

1:23:35.916 --> 1:23:38.375
It was an amazing tour.

1:23:38.458 --> 1:23:41.000
We were sort of, like,
in our own little world,

1:23:41.083 --> 1:23:43.125
not thinking about
the outside world.

1:23:43.208 --> 1:23:46.125
[upbeat disco music playing]

1:23:46.208 --> 1:23:50.292
♪ ♪

1:23:50.375 --> 1:23:53.292
[crowd roaring]

1:23:53.375 --> 1:24:00.375
♪ ♪

1:24:15.791 --> 1:24:18.333
- He struck him out,
and the ball game is over.

1:24:18.417 --> 1:24:21.167
[cheers and applause]

1:24:22.833 --> 1:24:26.375
- Okay, let's usher Steve
down to the explosives

1:24:26.458 --> 1:24:30.375
with a loud
"Disco sucks" chant.

1:24:30.458 --> 1:24:32.375
Disco sucks!

1:24:32.458 --> 1:24:34.583
all: Disco sucks!

1:24:34.666 --> 1:24:36.666
Disco sucks!

1:24:36.749 --> 1:24:38.833
Disco sucks!

1:24:38.916 --> 1:24:40.749
Disco sucks!

1:24:40.833 --> 1:24:42.250
Disco sucks!

1:24:42.333 --> 1:24:43.875
["You Should Be Dancing"
playing]

1:24:43.958 --> 1:24:45.541
- Ladies and gentlemen,
our brother Andy.

1:24:45.624 --> 1:24:48.583
[crowd cheering]

1:24:48.666 --> 1:24:50.583
♪ ♪

1:24:50.666 --> 1:24:52.541
♪ My baby moves at midnight ♪

1:24:52.624 --> 1:24:54.250
♪ ♪

1:24:54.333 --> 1:24:55.791
♪ Goes right on till the dawn ♪

1:24:55.875 --> 1:24:58.000
♪ ♪

1:24:58.083 --> 1:25:00.292
♪ My woman takes me higher ♪

1:25:00.375 --> 1:25:01.791
♪ ♪

1:25:01.875 --> 1:25:03.916
♪ My woman keeps me warm ♪

1:25:04.000 --> 1:25:05.916
♪ ♪

1:25:06.000 --> 1:25:08.000
all: ♪ What you doing
on your back? ♪

1:25:08.083 --> 1:25:09.292
♪ Oh-ho ♪

1:25:09.375 --> 1:25:11.916
♪ What you doing
on your back? ♪

1:25:12.000 --> 1:25:15.417
♪ Ah, you should be dancing ♪

1:25:15.499 --> 1:25:17.708
♪ Yeah ♪

1:25:17.791 --> 1:25:20.541
♪ Dancing, yeah ♪

1:25:20.624 --> 1:25:25.499
♪ ♪

1:25:25.583 --> 1:25:26.749
- Come on!

1:25:26.833 --> 1:25:28.541
- Andy joined us onstage
for "You Should Be Dancing,"

1:25:28.624 --> 1:25:30.958
and it was
the four of us together,

1:25:31.041 --> 1:25:32.583
and Andy joined my mic,

1:25:32.666 --> 1:25:34.458
so we were singing
around the one mic,

1:25:34.541 --> 1:25:36.666
and he kept looking up,
and he stood back and he goes,

1:25:36.749 --> 1:25:39.041
"Can you believe this shit?"

1:25:39.125 --> 1:25:41.250
all: ♪ Yeah ♪
- Come on.

1:25:41.333 --> 1:25:43.749
- Nobody could believe
what was going on.

1:25:43.833 --> 1:25:45.125
And to see
the four of us onstage,

1:25:45.208 --> 1:25:46.583
when I looked over
and saw Barry and Robin

1:25:46.666 --> 1:25:48.000
and I saw Andy in front of me,
I thought,

1:25:48.083 --> 1:25:50.458
"This is how it's gotta be."

1:25:50.541 --> 1:25:53.583
- ♪ Yeah ♪

1:25:53.666 --> 1:25:58.833
♪ ♪

1:25:58.916 --> 1:26:00.624
- How 'bout the Bee Gees?

1:26:00.708 --> 1:26:04.458
[crowd booing]

1:26:04.541 --> 1:26:06.292
Well, listen, we took
all the disco records

1:26:06.375 --> 1:26:08.499
that you brought tonight,

1:26:08.583 --> 1:26:11.708
threw 'em in a giant box,

1:26:11.791 --> 1:26:15.333
and we're gonna blow 'em up
real good.

1:26:15.417 --> 1:26:22.417
♪ ♪

1:26:25.749 --> 1:26:28.167
[fireworks popping]

1:26:28.250 --> 1:26:32.499
One, two, three, boom!

1:26:32.583 --> 1:26:35.041
[explosion booms]

1:26:35.125 --> 1:26:37.624
[cheers and applause]

1:26:37.708 --> 1:26:40.000
That blew 'em up real good!

1:26:40.083 --> 1:26:46.499
♪ ♪

1:26:46.583 --> 1:26:48.292
- ♪ Dance ♪

1:26:48.375 --> 1:26:51.167
- They'd tell you as an usher,
every now and then,

1:26:51.250 --> 1:26:53.125
you're gonna get
a drunk person

1:26:53.208 --> 1:26:54.833
storming the field.

1:26:54.916 --> 1:26:57.375
Try to grab 'em,
hold on to 'em, or whatever.

1:26:57.458 --> 1:27:00.167
But everybody ran on the field.

1:27:00.250 --> 1:27:02.749
- ♪ Dance ♪

1:27:02.833 --> 1:27:04.375
♪ Dance ♪

1:27:04.458 --> 1:27:06.250
♪ Dance ♪

1:27:06.333 --> 1:27:08.833
♪ Dance, dance ♪

1:27:08.916 --> 1:27:11.208
- When I got older,
I recognized

1:27:11.292 --> 1:27:15.708
that this was actually the end
of a era.

1:27:15.791 --> 1:27:17.208
- ♪ Dance ♪

1:27:17.292 --> 1:27:18.208
♪ Dance ♪

1:27:18.292 --> 1:27:19.708
- It was a book burning.

1:27:19.791 --> 1:27:22.167
It was a racist,

1:27:22.250 --> 1:27:25.041
homophobic book burning.

1:27:25.125 --> 1:27:28.666
And the Bee Gees
got caught up in that

1:27:28.749 --> 1:27:31.083
because they were
part of that culture

1:27:31.167 --> 1:27:33.875
that was lifting
a lot of people up.

1:27:33.958 --> 1:27:38.250
♪ ♪

1:27:38.333 --> 1:27:39.583
[cheers and applause]

1:27:39.666 --> 1:27:40.958
- Thank you.
We love you.

1:27:41.041 --> 1:27:43.333
And we'll see you again.
Bye-bye.

1:27:45.541 --> 1:27:48.458
[solemn music]

1:27:48.541 --> 1:27:49.916
♪ ♪

1:27:50.000 --> 1:27:53.791
- Nearly 7,000 spectators held
their very own demolition.

1:27:53.875 --> 1:27:56.666
Game two of the doubleheader
was canceled last night.

1:27:56.749 --> 1:28:00.208
That game will be forfeited.

1:28:00.292 --> 1:28:02.499
- The anti-disco movement

1:28:02.583 --> 1:28:05.083
was almost anti-Bee Gees
at that point.

1:28:05.167 --> 1:28:07.916
- Ironically, the soundtrack
to "Saturday Night Fever,"

1:28:08.000 --> 1:28:09.916
the album
that made them superstars,

1:28:10.000 --> 1:28:12.583
also branded them
as a disco group.

1:28:12.666 --> 1:28:14.250
- Because you can dance to it,
I mean,

1:28:14.333 --> 1:28:15.916
doesn't necessarily make it
a disco song.

1:28:16.000 --> 1:28:17.583
I mean, you can dance
to lots of songs.

1:28:17.666 --> 1:28:20.000
- You really don't wanna be
labeled "disco"...

1:28:20.083 --> 1:28:21.292
- No, no.
- At all, do you?

1:28:21.375 --> 1:28:23.000
- Because our music
is a variety

1:28:23.083 --> 1:28:24.250
of different kinds of music.

1:28:24.333 --> 1:28:25.958
It shouldn't be called
just that.

1:28:26.041 --> 1:28:28.000
- So people hated disco.

1:28:28.083 --> 1:28:30.167
Hated it.

1:28:30.250 --> 1:28:31.583
- We had FBI
and Secret Service

1:28:31.666 --> 1:28:33.624
around the airplane every time
we landed in a certain place

1:28:33.708 --> 1:28:35.458
'cause of the bomb threats.

1:28:35.541 --> 1:28:37.958
It was scary stuff.

1:28:38.041 --> 1:28:39.292
- We were perplexed,

1:28:39.375 --> 1:28:40.708
'cause I got that vibe
from them.

1:28:40.791 --> 1:28:42.499
You know,
"Why are people doing this?"

1:28:42.583 --> 1:28:44.250
- The Bee Gees claim

1:28:44.333 --> 1:28:46.458
some radio stations
around the country

1:28:46.541 --> 1:28:49.167
are refusing to play
their new single.

1:28:49.250 --> 1:28:50.458
- The Bee Gees are not allowed
to have a hit

1:28:50.541 --> 1:28:51.791
because they had
a lot of success

1:28:51.875 --> 1:28:52.958
with "Saturday Night Fever."

1:28:53.041 --> 1:28:54.125
That, to me, is crap.

1:28:54.208 --> 1:28:56.791
- Radio is, of course,
very difficult to get back

1:28:56.875 --> 1:28:58.250
once you lose them.

1:28:58.333 --> 1:29:00.541
Back then,
if you weren't on the radio,

1:29:00.624 --> 1:29:01.624
there was nothing.

1:29:01.708 --> 1:29:03.541
- Let's all grow up.
We're just a pop group.

1:29:03.624 --> 1:29:04.833
We're not a political force.

1:29:04.916 --> 1:29:06.333
We're just making music.

1:29:06.417 --> 1:29:07.916
But I don't think there's
any reason to chalk us off

1:29:08.000 --> 1:29:09.499
because we existed in the '70s

1:29:09.583 --> 1:29:11.499
and we would like to exist
in the '80s, you know.

1:29:11.583 --> 1:29:14.375
Does anybody mind if we exist
in the '80s, thank you?

1:29:14.458 --> 1:29:17.000
- It was so overwhelming,

1:29:17.083 --> 1:29:20.041
and the whole dynamic changed.

1:29:20.125 --> 1:29:22.791
- There were just crazy days.

1:29:22.875 --> 1:29:25.041
I preferred Maurice
as Maurice not being a Bee Gee,

1:29:25.125 --> 1:29:26.499
if that makes sense to you.

1:29:26.583 --> 1:29:30.041
I preferred him as Maurice,
not being a Bee Gee.

1:29:30.125 --> 1:29:31.708
- Suddenly, they realized

1:29:31.791 --> 1:29:34.000
that they were in
a different position.

1:29:34.083 --> 1:29:37.083
Robin went through a kind of--

1:29:37.167 --> 1:29:39.833
it wasn't a breakdown,
but it was just something

1:29:39.916 --> 1:29:43.208
where he felt very shy
of being in public

1:29:43.292 --> 1:29:45.417
and doing things for a while.

1:29:45.499 --> 1:29:48.041
- The backlash was
a very frightening experience.

1:29:48.125 --> 1:29:49.833
When things get to that point,

1:29:49.916 --> 1:29:53.208
you're out of control
of the whole thing.

1:29:53.292 --> 1:29:55.167
- We thought the Bee Gees
better go on the back burner

1:29:55.250 --> 1:29:57.375
for a while
until this dies down

1:29:57.458 --> 1:29:59.041
or something, you know.

1:29:59.125 --> 1:30:01.417
We couldn't do anything
as the Bee Gees at all.

1:30:01.499 --> 1:30:03.208
♪ ♪

1:30:03.292 --> 1:30:05.458
- Well, backlash,
I'm really good on.

1:30:09.666 --> 1:30:13.541
Any band that is successful

1:30:13.624 --> 1:30:16.499
is going to have

1:30:16.583 --> 1:30:20.208
some form of resist--
that's just the law of nature.

1:30:20.292 --> 1:30:21.208
[somber music]

1:30:21.292 --> 1:30:23.417
When they get so successful,

1:30:23.499 --> 1:30:24.916
sometimes the only
interesting thing

1:30:25.000 --> 1:30:27.292
to say about them is,
"Oh, I don't like them.

1:30:27.375 --> 1:30:29.458
"Everyone else likes, you know,
'How Deep Is Your Love.'

1:30:29.541 --> 1:30:32.333
I don't--
you know, it's stupid."

1:30:32.417 --> 1:30:34.250
For bands of my generation,

1:30:34.333 --> 1:30:36.250
you understand
about the ups and downs.

1:30:36.333 --> 1:30:38.583
You can see it.
Like, where are the pitfalls?

1:30:38.666 --> 1:30:40.916
What is the shit
you're gonna take?

1:30:41.000 --> 1:30:43.083
When might this happen?
When might that happen?

1:30:43.167 --> 1:30:44.958
For those people
that were on the first wave

1:30:45.041 --> 1:30:48.208
of sort of global
pop superstardom,

1:30:48.292 --> 1:30:49.958
if you wanna call it that,

1:30:50.041 --> 1:30:51.083
it was new to them.

1:30:51.167 --> 1:30:52.916
Like, "Why does everyone
suddenly hate our band?

1:30:53.000 --> 1:30:55.083
"We sold 8 billion records
last year.

1:30:55.167 --> 1:30:57.208
What's the deal?"

1:30:57.292 --> 1:30:59.458
So it's confusing.

1:30:59.541 --> 1:31:01.250
- It was not
just the Bee Gees

1:31:01.333 --> 1:31:05.791
but the idea of dance

1:31:05.875 --> 1:31:07.458
in that period,

1:31:07.541 --> 1:31:10.417
it was no longer acceptable

1:31:10.499 --> 1:31:13.000
for this kind of music
to carry the weight,

1:31:13.083 --> 1:31:15.000
to carry the industry.

1:31:15.083 --> 1:31:16.583
♪ ♪

1:31:16.666 --> 1:31:18.499
Everybody was at that point
in their lives

1:31:18.583 --> 1:31:22.375
where they began to look
for other things to do.

1:31:23.875 --> 1:31:26.417
And Andy was having
problems too.

1:31:26.499 --> 1:31:28.125
- Andy?
Andy...

1:31:28.208 --> 1:31:30.125
- I saw him in Malibu.

1:31:30.208 --> 1:31:31.250
He'd been involved

1:31:31.333 --> 1:31:33.624
with a lot of people
who were doing drugs,

1:31:33.708 --> 1:31:35.333
and he was doing drugs.

1:31:35.417 --> 1:31:37.791
He was doing cocaine.

1:31:37.875 --> 1:31:40.583
I talked to him
outside on the balcony,

1:31:40.666 --> 1:31:42.583
saying, you know, "This is
really a nice house, Andy.

1:31:42.666 --> 1:31:44.749
"It's a nice car out there,
that Porsche.

1:31:44.833 --> 1:31:46.000
"Really nice.

1:31:46.083 --> 1:31:48.375
You're not gonna keep all this,
you know."

1:31:48.458 --> 1:31:49.833
And he said,
"What do you mean?"

1:31:49.916 --> 1:31:51.833
I said,
"You do what you're doing,

1:31:51.916 --> 1:31:53.333
"this stuff will vanish.

1:31:53.417 --> 1:31:54.791
"All this stuff will go.

1:31:54.875 --> 1:31:57.167
Your career will go
out the window, everything."

1:31:57.250 --> 1:32:00.208
And he says, "I know. I know.
I know what I have to do."

1:32:00.292 --> 1:32:03.041
- There was a lot of chaos
that I didn't witness,

1:32:03.125 --> 1:32:05.666
but I was aware of it.

1:32:05.749 --> 1:32:07.000
We were scattered
all over the place

1:32:07.083 --> 1:32:08.333
for a little while.

1:32:08.417 --> 1:32:10.208
♪ ♪

1:32:10.292 --> 1:32:14.041
Robin was either in New York,
or Maurice was in England.

1:32:14.125 --> 1:32:15.499
I was alone at the time,

1:32:15.583 --> 1:32:18.000
and I got a phone call
from Barbra.

1:32:18.083 --> 1:32:20.708
♪ ♪

1:32:20.791 --> 1:32:23.333
She asked me
about writing songs for her,

1:32:23.417 --> 1:32:26.666
and that terrified me.

1:32:26.749 --> 1:32:29.375
I don't know if I can do this,
you know?

1:32:29.458 --> 1:32:30.708
So I called my brothers,

1:32:30.791 --> 1:32:33.375
and I said,
"This is what we gotta do.

1:32:33.458 --> 1:32:35.499
And let's do it."

1:32:35.583 --> 1:32:37.749
And that's how
the "Guilty" album came about.

1:32:37.833 --> 1:32:40.499
[Barry Gibb's "Woman in Love"]

1:32:40.583 --> 1:32:41.875
[acoustic pop music]

1:32:41.958 --> 1:32:44.833
We really could not get
on the radio.

1:32:44.916 --> 1:32:48.375
So the whole idea was
to write for other people.

1:32:48.458 --> 1:32:49.708
Let's be songwriters.

1:32:49.791 --> 1:32:52.417
Let's try and graduate
from being a group

1:32:52.499 --> 1:32:55.583
that's probably...

1:32:55.666 --> 1:32:58.000
beginning to fade, you know?

1:32:58.083 --> 1:33:00.708
Let's see if we can
dance around that.

1:33:00.791 --> 1:33:04.292
♪ Life is a moment in space ♪

1:33:04.375 --> 1:33:07.041
♪ When the dream is gone ♪

1:33:07.125 --> 1:33:10.208
♪ It's a lonelier place ♪

1:33:10.292 --> 1:33:12.583
- It was more about outlets
for writing,

1:33:12.666 --> 1:33:16.125
writing songs
that aren't Bee Gees songs.

1:33:16.208 --> 1:33:18.083
They have an attitude
somewhere else.

1:33:18.167 --> 1:33:19.833
- ♪ I stumble and fall ♪

1:33:19.916 --> 1:33:24.541
♪ But I give you it all ♪

1:33:24.624 --> 1:33:28.292
♪ I am a woman in love ♪

1:33:28.375 --> 1:33:30.417
♪ And I do anything ♪

1:33:30.499 --> 1:33:33.458
♪ To get you into my world ♪

1:33:33.541 --> 1:33:36.083
- Now, Robin, you and Barry
cowrote "Woman in Love,"

1:33:36.167 --> 1:33:38.541
which became
the international smash.

1:33:38.624 --> 1:33:41.208
Was it difficult
taking the woman's perspective?

1:33:41.292 --> 1:33:43.791
- Oh, no.
[laughter]

1:33:43.875 --> 1:33:45.250
- It's our way of doing things.

1:33:45.333 --> 1:33:46.292
We will assume that role

1:33:46.375 --> 1:33:47.916
within the song
to write the song.

1:33:48.000 --> 1:33:49.875
- After
the Barbra Streisand album,

1:33:49.958 --> 1:33:52.083
managers would call up
all the time:

1:33:52.167 --> 1:33:53.958
"Gee, can I get together
with you guys?

1:33:54.041 --> 1:33:55.333
Will you make my record?"

1:33:55.417 --> 1:33:56.833
And, you know,
established artists.

1:33:56.916 --> 1:33:58.333
- ♪ Oh ♪

1:33:58.417 --> 1:34:03.000
♪ Why do you have to be
a heartbreaker ♪

1:34:03.083 --> 1:34:04.541
♪ When I'm just being ♪

1:34:04.624 --> 1:34:06.749
♪ What you want me to be? ♪

1:34:06.833 --> 1:34:10.458
- ♪ Get in the middle
of a chain reaction ♪

1:34:10.541 --> 1:34:12.624
♪ You get a medal
when you're lost in action ♪

1:34:12.708 --> 1:34:13.791
- It was just as important
for us

1:34:13.875 --> 1:34:15.583
to have an artist singing
one of our songs

1:34:15.666 --> 1:34:18.333
and being on the radio
as it was for ourselves.

1:34:18.417 --> 1:34:19.916
both: ♪ Islands in the stream ♪

1:34:20.000 --> 1:34:21.958
♪ That is what we are ♪

1:34:22.041 --> 1:34:23.958
♪ No one in between ♪

1:34:24.041 --> 1:34:26.333
♪ How can we be wrong? ♪

1:34:26.417 --> 1:34:27.583
♪ Sail away with me ♪

1:34:27.666 --> 1:34:29.458
- When you write a song
with someone in mind

1:34:29.541 --> 1:34:31.000
that you really love

1:34:31.083 --> 1:34:33.833
and then that person ends up
singing it,

1:34:33.916 --> 1:34:35.624
there's no reward like it.

1:34:35.708 --> 1:34:40.208
- ♪ Immortality ♪

1:34:40.292 --> 1:34:41.833
♪ Oh, baby ♪

1:34:41.916 --> 1:34:45.541
♪ There is a vision
and a fire in me ♪

1:34:45.624 --> 1:34:47.624
♪ Oh ♪

1:34:47.708 --> 1:34:50.833
- We wrote so many
different types of song,

1:34:50.916 --> 1:34:53.666
and that created
that new determination

1:34:53.749 --> 1:34:56.833
for us to become
the Bee Gees again.

1:34:56.916 --> 1:34:59.333
all:
♪ When a lonely heart breaks ♪

1:34:59.417 --> 1:35:02.541
♪ It's the one that forsakes ♪

1:35:02.624 --> 1:35:05.833
♪ It's the dream
that we stole ♪

1:35:05.916 --> 1:35:07.583
- I think, over time,

1:35:07.666 --> 1:35:10.041
we became
more and more unified.

1:35:10.125 --> 1:35:11.499
By '85,

1:35:11.583 --> 1:35:13.041
we really got it together
as a group.

1:35:13.125 --> 1:35:15.167
♪ ♪

1:35:15.250 --> 1:35:17.791
We became a real band again.

1:35:17.875 --> 1:35:20.375
["For Whom the Bell Tolls"]

1:35:20.458 --> 1:35:23.541
all: ♪ For you, it's goodbye ♪

1:35:23.624 --> 1:35:25.708
♪ For me, it's to cry ♪

1:35:25.791 --> 1:35:29.749
♪ For whom the bell tolls ♪

1:35:29.833 --> 1:35:31.624
- We never really had
a category.

1:35:31.708 --> 1:35:33.875
We just had different periods,

1:35:33.958 --> 1:35:36.499
and we managed to fit
into different eras,

1:35:36.583 --> 1:35:38.375
and we saw a lot of people

1:35:38.458 --> 1:35:41.499
who were the champions
of their era come and go.

1:35:41.583 --> 1:35:44.499
We didn't always connect,
but we stayed around.

1:35:44.583 --> 1:35:46.791
We managed to defy
the criticism

1:35:46.875 --> 1:35:47.875
